{"title_page": "Robert Horn (water polo)", "text_new": "{{short description|American water polo player}}\n'''Robert \"Bob\" Martin Horn''' (November 1, 1931 &ndash; January 11, 2019)<ref name=\"Obituary\">[https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/bob-horn-u-s-olympic-and-ucla-mens-swimming-and-water-polo-coach-passes-away-at-87/ Robert Horn's obituary]</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[water polo]] player who competed in the [[1956 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1960 Summer Olympics]]. He was born in [[Minneapolis]].\n\nHorn went to [[Fullerton College]] and then [[California State University, Long Beach]] playing water polo at the later location. Horn was a member of the American water polo team which finished fifth in the [[Water polo at the 1956 Summer Olympics|1956 tournament]]. He played five matches as goalkeeper. Four year later he finished seventh with the American team in the [[Water polo at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960 tournament]]. He played four matches as goalkeeper. For 28 years Horn was water polo coach at UCLA.<ref>[http://www.waterpololegends.com/2008/07/bob-horn-legendary-coach-of-ucla.html UCLA water polo page on horn]</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ho/robert-horn-1.html Robert Horn's profile at Sports Reference.com]\n\n{{United States men's water polo squad 1956 Summer Olympics}}\n{{United States men's water polo squad 1960 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horn, Robert}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Long Beach State Beach men's water polo players]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins men's water polo coaches]]\n[[Category:American male water polo players]]\n[[Category:Olympic water polo players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Water polo players at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Water polo players at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{US-waterpolo-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American water polo player}}\n'''Robert \"Bob\" Martin Horn''' (November 1, 1931 &ndash; January 11, 2019)<ref name=\"Obituary\">[https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/bob-horn-u-s-olympic-and-ucla-mens-swimming-and-water-polo-coach-passes-away-at-87/ Robert Horn's obituary]</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[water polo]] player who competed in the [[1956 Summer Olympics]] and in the [[1960 Summer Olympics]]. He was born in [[Minneapolis]].\n\nHorn went to [[Fullerton College]] and then [[California State University, Long Beach]] playing water polo at the later location. Horn was a member of the American water polo team which finished fifth in the [[Water polo at the 1956 Summer Olympics|1956 tournament]]. He played five matches as goalkeeper. Four year later he finished seventh with the American team in the [[Water polo at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960 tournament]]. He played four matches as goalkeeper. For 28 years Horn was water polo coach at UCLA.<ref>[http://www.waterpololegends.com/2008/07/bob-horn-legendary-coach-of-ucla.html UCLA water polo page on horn]</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ho/robert-horn-1.html Robert Horn's profile at Sports Reference.com]\n\n{{United States men's water polo squad 1956 Summer Olympics}}\n{{United States men's water polo squad 1960 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horn, Robert}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Long Beach State Beach men's water polo players]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins men's water polo coaches]]\n[[Category:American male water polo players]]\n[[Category:Olympic water polo players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Water polo players at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Water polo players at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{US-waterpolo-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Landingdude13", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Horn_(water_polo)"}
{"title_page": "Macedonian Thrace Brewery", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Macedonian Thrace Brewery|timestamp=20200411031518|date=April 11, 2020|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Macedonian Thrace Brewery|date=April 11, 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox company\n| logo                = Vergina Beer Logo English.png\n| logo_caption        = Vergina Beer logo, signature brand of Macedonian Thrace Brewery\n| hq_location         = [[Komotini]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Greece]]\n| products            = Vergina Premium Lager<br />Vergina Red<br />Vergina Weiss<br />Vergina Porfyra<br />Vergina xxx Black<br />Thracian Malt\n| subsid              = Tuvunu S.A.\n}}\n\n'''Macedonian Thrace Brewery''' ({{Lang-el|\u0396\u03c5\u03b8\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03af\u03b1 \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u0398\u03c1\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}) is a Greek brewery, founded in 1996, based in [[Komotini]] and  '''Vergina Beer''' is its signature product. It also has branches in [[Athens]] and [[Thessaloniki]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verginabeer.com/en/contact|title=Contact form {{!}} Vergina Beer|website=www.verginabeer.com|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nA [[Greek Americans|Greek American]] [[chemical engineer]], Demetri Politopoulos, with a Diploma in Brewing Technology from [[Siebel Institute of Technology]] in Chicago,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessawardseurope.com/know/item/special-features-series-macedonian-thrace-brewery|title=2011 Ruban d'Honneur recipient for Entrepreneur of the year award: Macedonian Thrace Brewery|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and his brother during a trip to North Mexico, searching for investment opportunities, showed enthusiasm over the variety and the number of beer brands of the country. After returning to their hometown, [[Manhattan]], while they were having a conversation about beers they started wondering which beers were drinking while back in Greece. Soon, Demetri figured out none of the beer trademarks in Greece were actually having Greek interests and almost in every country a significant rate of the inland consumption of beer was fulfilled by local breweries.<ref name=\":0\" />  \n==== Establishment and release of Vergina Beer ====\nMacedonian Thrace Brewery S.A. was founded on February 1, 1996 and the Industrial area of [[Komotini]] was selected as the seat of the company facilities due to its infrastructures, the well organised business environment and its motives. The main goal of the newly founded company was the production of the \"first Greek beer\" under the trade name \"''Vergina\"'''''.''' Thus, the construction of the brewery began and lasted until the fall of 1997. After some problems at the production, Vergina Beer finally managed to release on February 18th,1998.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://tovima.dolnet.gr/print_article.php?e=B&f=14867&m=A10&aa=1|title=\u03a4\u03bf \u0392\u0397\u039c\u0391 onLine \u2013 \u03a1\u0395\u03a0\u039f\u03a1\u03a4\u0391\u0396|date=September 18, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070918085412/http://tovima.dolnet.gr/print_article.php?e=B&f=14867&m=A10&aa=1|access-date=April 9, 2020|archive-date=September 18, 2007}}</ref> Some of the difficulties occurred caused by the unfair competition tactics for which '''Athenian Brewery''', a [[Heineken N.V.|Heineken]] subsidiary company, later was found guilty by the court, but had already affected the growth of the company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jr|first=Landon Thomas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/12/business/dealbook/in-greece-brewers-woes-reflect-struggle-of-business-owners.html|title=In Greece, Brewer's Woes Reflect Struggle of Business Owners|date=December 11, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 9, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drinksint.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/7610/Heineken_loses_legal_battle_in_Greece.html|title=Heineken loses legal battle in Greece \u2013 Drinks International \u2013 The global choice for drinks buyers|website=drinksint.com|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heineken-nl-fine-idUSKBN0TL1I520151202|title=Heineken subsidiary handed 31.5&nbsp;million euro record Greek fine|date=December 2, 2015|agency=Reuters|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Nowadays, The market share of the company ranges between around 5 and 7 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ekathimerini.com/233337/article/ekathimerini/business/greece-going-beer-crazy-as-microbreweries-proliferate|title=Greece going beer crazy as microbreweries proliferate, Dimitra Manifava {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.protagon.gr/themata/to-topio-tis-biras-stin-ellada-44341363785|title=\u039f \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03bc\u03c0\u03af\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 {{!}} \u039a\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a4\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c6\u03cd\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7|website=Protagon.gr|language=el|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Awards ====\nIn 2011 Demetri Politopoulos, founder and CEO of the company, became the recipient of the ''Ruban D\u2019Honneur'' for the ''RSM International Entrepreneur of the Year'' category at the European Business Awards.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2015 Politopoulos was awarded the ''Commendation Medal Star of Merit and Honour'' by Defence Minister of that time Panos Kammenos \"in recognition of his distinguished services to the country and particularly for the enhancement of financial activity and employment in the broader region of borderline Thrace...\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mod.mil.gr/en/press-releases/award-commendation-medal-star-merit-and-honour-defence-minister-panos-kammenos|title=Award of the Commendation Medal Star of Merit and Honour by Defence Minister Panos Kammenos to Dimitrios Politopoulos|website=Ministry of National Defence|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=|title=|url=http://www.gmfus.org/sites/default/files/TLS%20Final%20Program%20Book2.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 '''Vergina Weiss''' won the Silver Medal and the second place for MTB in the \"Speciality Wheat Beer\" category at the [[Brewing Industry International Awards|International Brewing Awards]] competition, the oldest one since 1886.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brewingawards.org/awards/2013|title=Brewing Awards \u2013 Welcome to the International Brewing Awards, incorporating The International Cider Awards|website=brewingawards.org|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 and 2018 again Vergina Weiss won the Bronze and Silver Medal accordingly, in the \"South German-Style [[Hefeweizen]] Hell\" category at the [[European Beer Star]] competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.european-beer-star.com/ebs-en/presse-und-fotos/gewinnerlisten/|title=European Beer Star \u2013 List of winners|website=european-beer-star.com|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nThe Brewery mainly produces Vergina Premium Lager, Vergina Red, Vergina Weiss, Vergina Porfyra and Vergina XXX Black, but also is the producer for Edelsteiner, Hillas and Prost beer trademarks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://untappd.com/MacedonianThraceBrewerySA/beer|title=Untappd|last=Team|first=The Untappd|website=Untappd|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nVergina beer products are exported since 1999 in US, England, Italy, Australia, Japan, Netherlands, Turkey, Bulgaria, Cyprus and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voria.gr/article/i-vergina-kerdizi-edafos-ston-polemo-tis-agoras-mpiras|title=\u0397 \"\u0392\u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\" \u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b4\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03ad\u03b4\u03b1\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \"\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\" \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b1\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac\u03c2 \u03bc\u03c0\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2|last=Voria.gr|website=\u0397 \u00ab\u0392\u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u00bb \u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b4\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03ad\u03b4\u03b1\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u00ab\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\u00bb \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b1\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac\u03c2 \u03bc\u03c0\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greeka.com/greece-culture/gastronomy/greek-beer/|title=Beers of Greece \u2013 Greek Gastronomy {{!}} Greeka.com|website=Greekacom|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n== References List ==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Breweries in Greece]]\n[[Category:Beer in Greece]]\n[[Category:Greek brands]]\n[[Category:Komotini]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Macedonian Thrace Brewery|timestamp=20200411031518|date=April 11, 2020|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Macedonian Thrace Brewery|date=April 11, 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox company\n| logo                = Vergina Beer Logo English.png\n| logo_caption        = Vergina Beer logo, signature brand of Macedonian Thrace Brewery\n| hq_location         = [[Komotini]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Greece]]\n| products            = Vergina premium lager<br />Vergina Red<br />Vergina Weiss<br />Vergina Porfyra<br />Vergina xxx black<br />Thracian Malt\n| subsid              = TUVUNU S.A.\n}}\n\n'''Macedonian Thrace Brewery''' ({{Lang-el|\u0396\u03c5\u03b8\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03af\u03b1 \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u0398\u03c1\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}) is a Greek brewery, founded in 1996, based in [[Komotini]] and  '''Vergina Beer''' is its signature product. It also has branches in [[Athens]] and [[Thessaloniki]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verginabeer.com/en/contact|title=Contact form {{!}} Vergina Beer|website=www.verginabeer.com|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nA [[Greek Americans|Greek American]] [[chemical engineer]], Demetri Politopoulos, with a Diploma in Brewing Technology from [[Siebel Institute of Technology]] in Chicago,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessawardseurope.com/know/item/special-features-series-macedonian-thrace-brewery|title=2011 Ruban d'Honneur recipient for Entrepreneur of the year award: Macedonian Thrace Brewery|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and his brother during a trip to North Mexico, searching for investment opportunities, showed enthusiasm over the variety and the number of beer brands of the country. After returning to their hometown, [[Manhattan]], while they were having a conversation about beers they started wondering which beers were drinking while back in Greece. Soon, Demetri figured out none of the beer trademarks in Greece were actually having Greek interests and almost in every country a significant rate of the inland consumption of beer was fulfilled by local breweries.<ref name=\":0\" />  \n==== Establishment and release of Vergina Beer ====\nMacedonian Thrace Brewery S.A. was founded on February 1, 1996 and the Industrial area of [[Komotini]] was selected as the seat of the company facilities due to its infrastructures, the well organised business environment and its motives. The main goal of the newly founded company was the production of the \"first Greek beer\" under the trade name \"''Vergina\"'''''.''' Thus, the construction of the brewery began and lasted until the fall of 1997. After some problems at the production, Vergina Beer finally managed to release on February 18th,1998.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://tovima.dolnet.gr/print_article.php?e=B&f=14867&m=A10&aa=1|title=\u03a4\u03bf \u0392\u0397\u039c\u0391 onLine \u2013 \u03a1\u0395\u03a0\u039f\u03a1\u03a4\u0391\u0396|date=September 18, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070918085412/http://tovima.dolnet.gr/print_article.php?e=B&f=14867&m=A10&aa=1|access-date=April 9, 2020|archive-date=September 18, 2007}}</ref> Some of the difficulties occurred caused by the unfair competition tactics for which '''Athenian Brewery''', a [[Heineken N.V.|Heineken]] subsidiary company, later was found guilty by the court, but had already affected the growth of the company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jr|first=Landon Thomas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/12/business/dealbook/in-greece-brewers-woes-reflect-struggle-of-business-owners.html|title=In Greece, Brewer's Woes Reflect Struggle of Business Owners|date=December 11, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 9, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drinksint.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/7610/Heineken_loses_legal_battle_in_Greece.html|title=Heineken loses legal battle in Greece \u2013 Drinks International \u2013 The global choice for drinks buyers|website=drinksint.com|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heineken-nl-fine-idUSKBN0TL1I520151202|title=Heineken subsidiary handed 31.5&nbsp;million euro record Greek fine|date=December 2, 2015|agency=Reuters|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Nowadays, The market share of the company ranges between around 5 and 7 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ekathimerini.com/233337/article/ekathimerini/business/greece-going-beer-crazy-as-microbreweries-proliferate|title=Greece going beer crazy as microbreweries proliferate, Dimitra Manifava {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.protagon.gr/themata/to-topio-tis-biras-stin-ellada-44341363785|title=\u039f \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03bc\u03c0\u03af\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 {{!}} \u039a\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a4\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c6\u03cd\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7|website=Protagon.gr|language=el|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Awards ====\nIn 2011 Demetri Politopoulos, founder and CEO of the company, became the recipient of the ''Ruban D\u2019Honneur'' for the ''RSM International Entrepreneur of the Year'' category at the European Business Awards.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2015 Politopoulos was awarded the ''Commendation Medal Star of Merit and Honour'' by Defence Minister of that time Panos Kammenos \"in recognition of his distinguished services to the country and particularly for the enhancement of financial activity and employment in the broader region of borderline Thrace...\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mod.mil.gr/en/press-releases/award-commendation-medal-star-merit-and-honour-defence-minister-panos-kammenos|title=Award of the Commendation Medal Star of Merit and Honour by Defence Minister Panos Kammenos to Dimitrios Politopoulos|website=Ministry of National Defence|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=|title=|url=http://www.gmfus.org/sites/default/files/TLS%20Final%20Program%20Book2.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 '''Vergina Weiss''' won the Silver Medal and the second place for MTB in the \"Speciality Wheat Beer\" category at the [[Brewing Industry International Awards|International Brewing Awards]] competition, the oldest one since 1886.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brewingawards.org/awards/2013|title=Brewing Awards \u2013 Welcome to the International Brewing Awards, incorporating The International Cider Awards|website=brewingawards.org|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 and 2018 again Vergina Weiss won the Bronze and Silver Medal accordingly, in the \"South German-Style [[Hefeweizen]] Hell\" category at the [[European Beer Star]] competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.european-beer-star.com/ebs-en/presse-und-fotos/gewinnerlisten/|title=European Beer Star \u2013 List of winners|website=european-beer-star.com|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nThe Brewery mainly produces Vergina Premium Lager, Vergina Red, Vergina Weiss, Vergina Porfyra and Vergina XXX Black, but also is the producer for Edelsteiner, Hillas and Prost beer trademarks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://untappd.com/MacedonianThraceBrewerySA/beer|title=Untappd|last=Team|first=The Untappd|website=Untappd|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nVergina beer products are exported since 1999 in US, England, Italy, Australia, Japan, Netherlands, Turkey, Bulgaria, Cyprus and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voria.gr/article/i-vergina-kerdizi-edafos-ston-polemo-tis-agoras-mpiras|title=\u0397 \"\u0392\u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\" \u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b4\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03ad\u03b4\u03b1\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \"\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\" \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b1\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac\u03c2 \u03bc\u03c0\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2|last=Voria.gr|website=\u0397 \u00ab\u0392\u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u00bb \u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b4\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03ad\u03b4\u03b1\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u00ab\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\u00bb \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b1\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac\u03c2 \u03bc\u03c0\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greeka.com/greece-culture/gastronomy/greek-beer/|title=Beers of Greece \u2013 Greek Gastronomy {{!}} Greeka.com|website=Greekacom|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n== References List ==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Breweries in Greece]]\n[[Category:Beer in Greece]]\n[[Category:Greek brands]]\n[[Category:Komotini]]\n", "name_user": "Gnslps", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Macedonian_Thrace_Brewery"}
{"title_page": "Space Station 13", "text_new": "{{Unreliable sources|date=May 2019}}\n{{italics}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Space Station 13\n| image = Space station 13 logo.png\n| developer = Originally developed by Exadv1, now multiple\n| engine = BYOND\n| released = 16 February 2003\n| genre = [[Role-playing video game|Roleplaying]], [[Sandbox video game|Sandbox]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer]]\n}}\n<!-- Keep controversies concerning individual server communities out of the article. -->\n'''''Space Station 13''''' (or '''''SS13''''') is a [[top-down perspective|top-down]] tile based [[role-playing video game|role-playing]] [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] [[video game]] running on the [[BYOND]] [[game engine]], originally released in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.byond.com/games/Exadv1/SpaceStation13 |title=Space Station 13 by Exadv1 at BYOND Games |publisher=Byond.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThe game is generally set on a futuristic [[space station]], although certain player communities feature different settings, including [[spacecraft]] and [[exoplanet]]<nowiki/>s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.baystation12.net/SEV_Torch|title=SEV Torch - Baystation 12|website=wiki.baystation12.net|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.baystation12.net/Guide_to_Exploration|title=Guide to Exploration - Baystation 12|website=wiki.baystation12.net|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> The game is defined by its emphasis on player roles: at the start of every round, players choose from various roles and attempt to either help or hinder others' progress.\n\n==Gameplay==\nSpace Station 13 is generally played in rounds that are isolated from each other: actions do not persist canonically between rounds. At the beginning of each round, players are given time to either create a customized character using a character sheet or they may begin playing with a completely randomly generated character. Players can choose different jobs, such as [[janitor]] or [[engineer]], which dictate their role and responsibilities. The game is akin to a [[roleplaying]] [[sandbox game]], with events in each round largely being player-dictated.\n\nThe player can examine and use almost any object or being on the station, and is almost always context-sensitive. Different results will occur depending on many variables in any given interaction (e.g. Using a [[Crowbar (tool)|crowbar]] on another player would attack them but using it on a floorboard would pry it up). Additionally, the player can change their 'intent' between four different states (Help, Disarm, Grab, Harm) which will further influence actions taken. For example, using an empty hand on another player with help intent would cause you to hug them, but would cause you to punch them on Harm intent.\n\nThe game engine fully simulates power, biology, atmosphere, chemistry, and other complex object and environmental interactions beyond the vast majority of video games, which, to many people, compensates for its lack of visual quality and speed.\n\nWhile different [[Game server|servers]] may have their unique station constructs, generally there are eight [[Departmentalization|departments]] aboard the station. Supply and Service are also often grouped in the Civilian category.\n\n* Command (taking leadership roles aboard the station).\n* Security (enforcing [[Law|the law]], keeping peace and responding to emergencies aboard the station).\n* Engineering (generating power and keeping utilities maintained aboard the station, such as keeping doors functional and ensuring Oxygen is present around the station).\n* Science (researching technologies and developing '[[cyborg|Synthetic]]s' aboard the station).\n* Medical (keeping the crew healthy, performing most [[Surgery|surgeries]], researching [[disease]]s and creating [[Cloning|clones]] for deceased players aboard the station).\n* Supply ([[mining]] for [[minerals]] on a nearby planet, and taking charge of the cargo, such as purchasing goods for crew-members and sorting through all disposed items).\n* Service (keeping the station clean and providing food and drinks for the crew.).\n* Synthetics/Silicons (consisting of the station's [[Artificial intelligence|A.I]] and cyborgs, who are often bound by the [[Three Laws of Robotics]], which restrict AI from committing illegal acts, such as assaulting a crew member, unless someone changes said laws).\n\nOptimally, all players spawn at the beginning of each round and perform their jobs. However, randomly selected players are chosen to spawn as '[[antagonist|antagonists]]' aboard the station. Antagonists can range from mostly normal characters with certain malicious intentions, rogue [[artificial intelligence]]<nowiki/>s, and a wide assortment of monsters and enemies, such as [[Shapeshifting|changeling]]s, [[Alien (creature in Alien franchise)|aliens]], [[Lovecraftian horror|Lovecraftian horrors]], [[assassination|assassins]], and [[Death Squad|death squads]] armed with [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear weapons]]. It can be difficult for normal crew members to identify antagonists, and even harder to determine their objectives.\n\nDue to the presence of antagonists (and, sometimes, due to players failing at their jobs), many rounds escalate into chaos and disorder. While some communities have pre-set match timings, often rounds are concluded when the situation becomes critical and evacuation procedures are initiated.\n\n==Plot==\n\nDue to each server's lack of an agreed canonical storyline, most if not all servers have individualized lores and [[backstories]]. Generally though, Space Station 13 takes place in the 26th century on a research station owned by the [[megacorporation]] known as Nanotrasen. The station exists to research the recently discovered mineral 'plasma' (or 'phoron' on some servers), whose uses and properties Nanotrasen lacks knowledge of. Nanotrasen's influence and power have effectively made them a [[government]] entity, but is often left ambiguous as to whether they are good, evil or a neutral party (depending on the server). \n\nDue to Nanotrasen's immense stature and massive monopoly on plasma, it is targeted by an array of third-party aggressors. This includes, but is not limited to: the Syndicate (a coalition of smaller companies and planetary governments), the Space Wizard Federation (a federal group of [[thaumaturgy|thaumaturgical]] aggressors), Changelings (an extraterrestrial species with the ability to take on the form of any organic life-form they've 'absorbed') etc.\n\n==Development==\nSpace Station 13 was originally developed as an atmospherics simulator by Exadv1 in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.byond.com/members/Exadv1 |title=Exadv1 - Creations |publisher=Byond.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref>\nIts [[Closed source software|closed source]] codebase was allegedly stolen and [[Internet leak|leaked onto the internet]] in 2006, giving rise to SS13's current popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tgstation13.org/wiki/index.php/The_history_of_SS13 |title=The history of SS13 - /tg/station 13 Wiki |publisher=Tgstation13.org |date=2015-01-14 |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref> However, in a 2017 interview, Exadv1 claimed no theft actually took place, as he had voluntarily given the code to fellow programmers after ceasing work on the game due to personal circumstances.<ref>{{Citation|last=BlackPantsLegion|title=Space Station 13 Interview: Exadv1 (Yes, HIM)!|date=2017-10-21|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hP5t1b1TKQg|accessdate=2017-11-09}}</ref>\n\nA large number of promising community efforts to remake SS13 have been started over the years due to longstanding frustration with SS13's closed-source engine and low quality of code. Most of these attempts have since been abandoned, and a community mythos has jokingly built up around \"The Curse\", a supposed force that is responsible for the death of all attempts to remake the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=The curse of Space Station 13 |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-11-29-the-curse-of-space-station-13 |website=Eurogamer.net |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nRegardless, three major SS13 remakes are currently in development: Space Station 14<ref>[https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/01/20/space-station-13-remake-open-sourced/ Evac Shuttle: Space Station 13 Remake Open-Sourced] by Alice O'Connor on [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] (January 20, 2015)</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Space Station 14 |website=Space Station 14 |url=https://spacestation14.io/about/ |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>, Unitystation<ref>{{cite web |title=Unitystation on Steam |url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/801140/unitystation/ |website=Steam |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>, and Re:SS3D<ref>{{cite web |title=About Re:SS3D |url=https://ss3d.space/about/ |website=Re:SS3D |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n== Reception ==\n''Space Station 13'' garnered attention from various [[video game journalism]] websites over the years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamesn.com/indie/space-station-13-multiplayer-space-station-simulator-about-monkeys-insane-ai-cultists-and-paperwork |title=Space Station 13: a multiplayer space station simulator about monkeys, insane AI, cultists and paperwork |publisher=[[PCGamesN]] |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Quintin |url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2010/07/21/space-station-13-galactic-bartender-ep-1/ |title=Space Station 13: Galactic Bartender Ep. 1 |publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |date=2010-07-21 |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/space-station-13/3030-32586/ |title=Space Station 13 (Game) |publisher=[[Giant Bomb]] |date=2015-05-22 |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/tag/space-station-13/ |title=Space Station 13 &#124; Rock, Paper, Shotgun - PC Game Reviews, Previews, Subjectivity |publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref> The game has experienced an increasing player count as of recent, reaching more than 1500 players on at a single time by May 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.byond.com/games/?sort=live |title=BYOND Games - Make & Play Online Multiplayer Games |publisher=Byond.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref> Its popularity has gained it communities from websites such as [[4chan]], [[Reddit]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/SS13/ |title=Space Station 13 |publisher=Reddit.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref> the [[Facepunch Studios|Facepunch Studios forums]] and [[Something Awful]]. The game was also mentioned by [[Eurogamer]] as an inspiration for the now-cancelled<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-03-07-ion-the-space-survival-game-by-dean-hall-and-improbable-is-dead|title=Ion, the space survival game by Dean Hall and Improbable, is dead |last=Purchese |first=Robert |date=2017-03-07|website=[[Eurogamer]]|language=en-UK|access-date=2017-03-07}}</ref> game ION by [[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]] creator Dean \"Rocket\" Hall.<ref>{{cite web|last1=PULLAR-STRECKER|first1=Tom|title=Kiwi DayZ creator Dean Hall moves from zombies to space stations with Ion|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/technology/games/69551740/kiwi-dayz-creator-dean-hall-moves-from-zombies-to-space-stations-with-ion.html |website=Stuff.co.nz|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref> [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] named Space Station 13 on place 37 of its list of \"The 50 Best Free games on PC\" (of all time) in 2016<ref>[https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/10/31/the-50-best-free-games-on-pc/16/ 36. Space Station 13 [Official site) (2003) - Developer: Robust Games] on [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] (2016)</ref> and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/07/25/best-free-pc-games-for-2019/#Space_Station_13|title=Best Free PC Games for 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Rock Paper Shotgun|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209001932/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/07/25/best-free-pc-games-for-2019/#Space_Station_13|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of open source games]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://spacestation13.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Space MOGs]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Open-source video games]]\n[[Category:Simulation video games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Top-down video games]]\n[[Category:Open-source role-playing video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreliable sources|date=May 2019}}\n{{italics}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Space Station 13\n| image = Space station 13 logo.png\n| developer = Originally developed by Exadv1, now multiple\n| engine = BYOND\n| released = 16 February 2003\n| genre = [[Role-playing video game|Roleplaying]], [[Sandbox video game|Sandbox]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer]]\n}}\n<!-- Keep controversies concerning individual server communities out of the article. -->\n'''''Space Station 13''''' (or '''''SS13''''') is a [[top-down perspective|top-down]] tile based [[role-playing video game|role-playing]] [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] [[video game]] running on the [[BYOND]] [[game engine]], originally released in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.byond.com/games/Exadv1/SpaceStation13 |title=Space Station 13 by Exadv1 at BYOND Games |publisher=Byond.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThe game is generally set on a futuristic [[space station]], although certain player communities feature different settings, including [[spacecraft]] and [[exoplanet]]<nowiki/>s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.baystation12.net/SEV_Torch|title=SEV Torch - Baystation 12|website=wiki.baystation12.net|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.baystation12.net/Guide_to_Exploration|title=Guide to Exploration - Baystation 12|website=wiki.baystation12.net|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> The game is defined by its emphasis on player roles: at the start of every round, players choose from various roles and attempt to either help or hinder others' progress.\n\n==Gameplay==\nSpace Station 13 is generally played in rounds that are isolated from each other: actions do not persist canonically between rounds. At the beginning of each round, players are given time to either create a customized character using a character sheet or they may begin playing with a completely randomly generated character. Players can choose different jobs, such as [[janitor]] or [[engineer]], which dictate their role and responsibilities. The game is akin to a [[roleplaying]] [[sandbox game]], with events in each round largely being player-dictated.\n\nThe player can examine and use almost any object or being on the station, and is almost always context-sensitive. Different results will occur depending on many variables in any given interaction (e.g. Using a [[Crowbar (tool)|crowbar]] on another player would attack them but using it on a floorboard would pry it up). Additionally, the player can change their 'intent' between four different states (Help, Disarm, Grab, Harm) which will further influence actions taken. For example, using an empty hand on another player with help intent would cause you to hug them, but would cause you to punch them on Harm intent.\n\nThe game engine fully simulates power, biology, atmosphere, chemistry, and other complex object and environmental interactions beyond the vast majority of video games, which, to many people, compensates for its lack of visual quality and speed.\n\nWhile different [[Game server|servers]] may have their unique station constructs, generally there are eight [[Departmentalization|departments]] aboard the station. Supply and Service are also often grouped in the Civilian category.\n\n* Command (taking leadership roles aboard the station).\n* Security (enforcing [[Law|the law]], keeping peace and responding to emergencies aboard the station).\n* Engineering (generating power and keeping utilities maintained aboard the station, such as keeping doors functional and ensuring Oxygen is present around the station).\n* Science (researching technologies and developing '[[cyborg|Synthetic]]s' aboard the station).\n* Medical (keeping the crew healthy, performing most [[Surgery|surgeries]], researching [[disease]]s and creating [[Cloning|clones]] for deceased players aboard the station).\n* Supply ([[mining]] for [[minerals]] on a nearby planet, and taking charge of the cargo, such as purchasing goods for crew-members and sorting through all disposed items).\n* Service (keeping the station clean and providing food and drinks for the crew.).\n* Synthetics/Silicons (consisting of the station's [[Artificial intelligence|A.I]] and cyborgs, who are often bound by the [[Three Laws of Robotics]], which restrict AI from committing illegal acts, such as assaulting a crew member, unless someone changes said laws).\n\nOptimally, all players spawn at the beginning of each round and perform their jobs. However, randomly selected players are chosen to spawn as '[[antagonist|antagonists]]' aboard the station. Antagonists can range from mostly normal characters with certain malicious intentions, rogue [[artificial intelligence]]<nowiki/>s, and a wide assortment of monsters and enemies, such as [[Shapeshifting|changeling]]s, [[Alien (creature in Alien franchise)|aliens]], [[Lovecraftian horror|Lovecraftian horrors]], [[assassination|assassins]], and [[Death Squad|death squads]] armed with [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear weapons]]. It can be difficult for normal crew members to identify antagonists, and even harder to determine their objectives.\n\nDue to the presence of antagonists (and, sometimes, due to players failing at their jobs), many rounds escalate into chaos and disorder. While some communities have pre-set match timings, often rounds are concluded when the situation becomes critical and evacuation procedures are initiated.\n\n==Plot==\n\nDue to each server's lack of an agreed canonical storyline, most if not all servers have individualized lores and [[backstories]]. Generally though, Space Station 13 takes place in the 26th century on a research station owned by the [[megacorporation]] known as Nanotrasen. The station exists to research the recently discovered mineral 'plasma' (or 'phoron' on some servers), whose uses and properties Nanotrasen lacks knowledge of. Nanotrasen's influence and power have effectively made them a [[government]] entity, but is often left ambiguous as to whether they are good, evil or a neutral party (depending on the server). \n\nDue to Nanotrasen's immense stature and massive monopoly on plasma, it is targeted by an array of third-party aggressors. This includes, but is not limited to: the Syndicate (a coalition of smaller companies and planetary governments), the Space Wizard Federation (a federal group of [[thaumaturgy|thaumaturgical]] aggressors), Changelings (an extraterrestrial species with the ability to take on the form of any organic life-form they've 'absorbed') etc.\n\n==Development==\nSpace Station 13 was originally developed in 2003 as an atmospherics simulator by Exadv1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.byond.com/members/Exadv1 |title=Exadv1 - Creations |publisher=Byond.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref>\nIts [[Closed source software|closed source]] codebase was allegedly stolen and [[Internet leak|leaked onto the internet]] in 2006, giving rise to SS13's current popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tgstation13.org/wiki/index.php/The_history_of_SS13 |title=The history of SS13 - /tg/station 13 Wiki |publisher=Tgstation13.org |date=2015-01-14 |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref> However, in a 2017 interview, Exadv1 claimed no theft actually took place, as he had voluntarily given the code to fellow programmers after ceasing work on the game due to personal circumstances.<ref>{{Citation|last=BlackPantsLegion|title=Space Station 13 Interview: Exadv1 (Yes, HIM)!|date=2017-10-21|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hP5t1b1TKQg|accessdate=2017-11-09}}</ref>\n\nA large number of promising community efforts to remake SS13 have been started over the years due to longstanding frustration with SS13's closed-source engine and low quality of code. Most of these attempts have since been abandoned, and a community mythos has jokingly built up around \"The Curse\", a supposed force that is responsible for the death of all attempts to remake the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=The curse of Space Station 13 |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-11-29-the-curse-of-space-station-13 |website=Eurogamer.net |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nRegardless, three major SS13 remakes are currently in development: Space Station 14<ref>[https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/01/20/space-station-13-remake-open-sourced/ Evac Shuttle: Space Station 13 Remake Open-Sourced] by Alice O'Connor on [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] (January 20, 2015)</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Space Station 14 |website=Space Station 14 |url=https://spacestation14.io/about/ |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>, Unitystation<ref>{{cite web |title=Unitystation on Steam |url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/801140/unitystation/ |website=Steam |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>, and Re:SS3D<ref>{{cite web |title=About Re:SS3D |url=https://ss3d.space/about/ |website=Re:SS3D |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n== Reception ==\n''Space Station 13'' garnered attention from various [[video game journalism]] websites over the years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamesn.com/indie/space-station-13-multiplayer-space-station-simulator-about-monkeys-insane-ai-cultists-and-paperwork |title=Space Station 13: a multiplayer space station simulator about monkeys, insane AI, cultists and paperwork |publisher=[[PCGamesN]] |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Quintin |url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2010/07/21/space-station-13-galactic-bartender-ep-1/ |title=Space Station 13: Galactic Bartender Ep. 1 |publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |date=2010-07-21 |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/space-station-13/3030-32586/ |title=Space Station 13 (Game) |publisher=[[Giant Bomb]] |date=2015-05-22 |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/tag/space-station-13/ |title=Space Station 13 &#124; Rock, Paper, Shotgun - PC Game Reviews, Previews, Subjectivity |publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref> The game has experienced an increasing player count as of recent, reaching more than 1500 players on at a single time by May 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.byond.com/games/?sort=live |title=BYOND Games - Make & Play Online Multiplayer Games |publisher=Byond.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref> Its popularity has gained it communities from websites such as [[4chan]], [[Reddit]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/SS13/ |title=Space Station 13 |publisher=Reddit.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref> the [[Facepunch Studios|Facepunch Studios forums]] and [[Something Awful]]. The game was also mentioned by [[Eurogamer]] as an inspiration for the now-cancelled<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-03-07-ion-the-space-survival-game-by-dean-hall-and-improbable-is-dead|title=Ion, the space survival game by Dean Hall and Improbable, is dead |last=Purchese |first=Robert |date=2017-03-07|website=[[Eurogamer]]|language=en-UK|access-date=2017-03-07}}</ref> game ION by [[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]] creator Dean \"Rocket\" Hall.<ref>{{cite web|last1=PULLAR-STRECKER|first1=Tom|title=Kiwi DayZ creator Dean Hall moves from zombies to space stations with Ion|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/technology/games/69551740/kiwi-dayz-creator-dean-hall-moves-from-zombies-to-space-stations-with-ion.html |website=Stuff.co.nz|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref> [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] named Space Station 13 on place 37 of its list of \"The 50 Best Free games on PC\" (of all time) in 2016<ref>[https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/10/31/the-50-best-free-games-on-pc/16/ 36. Space Station 13 [Official site) (2003) - Developer: Robust Games] on [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] (2016)</ref> and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/07/25/best-free-pc-games-for-2019/#Space_Station_13|title=Best Free PC Games for 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Rock Paper Shotgun|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209001932/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/07/25/best-free-pc-games-for-2019/#Space_Station_13|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of open source games]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://spacestation13.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Space MOGs]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Open-source video games]]\n[[Category:Simulation video games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Top-down video games]]\n[[Category:Open-source role-playing video games]]\n", "name_user": "Acvzy", "label": "safe", "comment": "small flow edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_Station_13"}
{"title_page": "Mellisa Hollingsworth", "text_new": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Mellisa Hollingsworth\n| image          = Mellisa Hollingsworth at OP 2010.jpg\n| image_size     = 220\n| caption        = Hollingsworth in Calgary (2010)\n| headercolor    = lightsteelblue\n| birth_date     = {{birth-date and age|October 4, 1980}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lacombe, Alberta]], Canada\n| website        = {{URL|http://www.melhollingsworth.ca|MelHollingsworth.ca}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|[[Skeleton (sport)|Skeleton]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{CAN}} }}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2006 Winter Olympics|2006 Turin]]|[[Skeleton at the 2006 Winter Olympics&nbsp;\u2013 Women's|Women]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBT World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIBT World Championships 2000|2000 Igls]]|Women}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIBT World Championships 2012|2012 Lake Placid]]|Women}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIBT World Championships 2011|2011 K\u00f6nigssee]]|Women}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIBT World Championships 2011|2011 K\u00f6nigssee]]|Mixed team}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIBT World Championships 2012|2012 Lake Placid]]|Mixed team}}\n}}\n\n'''Mellisa Hollingsworth''' (born October 4, 1980 in [[Lacombe, Alberta]]) is a retired [[Canadians|Canadian]] athlete who competed from 1995-2014. She won the bronze medal in the [[Skeleton at the 2006 Winter Olympics|women's skeleton event]] at the [[2006 Winter Olympics]] in [[Turin]].\n\nHollingsworth also won a silver in the women's skeleton event at the [[FIBT World Championships 2000|2000 FIBT World Championships]] in [[Igls]], [[Austria]]. She won the women's [[List of Skeleton World Cup champions|Skeleton World Cup]] overall title both in [[2005/2006 Skeleton World Cup|2005-6]] and in [[2009-10 Skeleton World Cup|2009\u201310]].\n\nHollingsworth is the cousin of [[Ryan Davenport]], who won three medals in the men's skeleton event at the [[FIBT World Championships]] in the late 1990s.\n\nHollingsworth participated in the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia. After three runs, she was in second position behind [[Amy Williams]] of Great Britain. However, in the final run, despite a personal best start time of 4.93 seconds, Hollingsworth fell behind and ended up finishing fifth overall.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Hollingsworth falls short of podium |url=http://www.ctvolympics.ca/skeleton/news/newsid=46861.html|publisher=CTV Olympics|date=2010-02-19|accessdate=2010-02-19|author=Jeff Blair and Allan Maki}}</ref>\n\nHollingsworth retired after participating in the [[2014 Winter Olympic Games]] in Sochi, Russia.  <ref>{{Cite web|title=Mellisa Hollingsworth begins her last medal mission |url=https://www.reddeeradvocate.com/news/mellisa-hollingsworth-begins-her-last-medal-mission/|publisher=Red-Deer-Advocate}}</ref>\n\nIn summer 2018, Hollingsworth competed on ''[[The Amazing Race Canada 6|The Amazing Race Canada: Heroes Edition]]'' with barrel racer Nancy Csabay.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Barrel Racer Takes on The Amazing Race Canada |url=https://horse-canada.com/star-crossed-horses/barrel-racer-takes-on-the-amazing-race-canada/|publisher=Horse-Canada|date=2018-08-20|accessdate=2018-08-29}}</ref> They finished in 5th place.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Amazing Race Canada: Muertos and mercado in Mexico City |url=https://www.tv-eh.com/2018/08/28/amazing-race-canada-3-mexico-city/|publisher=TV, eh?|date=2018-08-28|accessdate=2018-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mellisa Hollingsworth}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.melhollingsworth.ca}}\n* {{COC profile|mellisa-hollingsworth}}\n* {{IOC profile|mellisa-hollingsworth}}\n* {{SR/Olympics profile|ho/mellisa-hollingsworth-richards-1|Mellisa Hollingsworth-Richards}}\n* {{IBSF|100564|Mellisa Hollingsworth}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20030509075908/http://www.davenportsleds.ca/phryanmh.htm Picture of Davenport and Hollingsworth (davenportsleds.ca)]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111105170232/http://sports123.com/ske/wwc.html |title=List of women's skeleton World Cup champions since 1997 (sports123.com)}}\n* [http://sports123.com/ske/wo.html Women's skeleton Olympic medalists since 2002 (sports123.com)]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304035143/http://sports123.com/ske/ww.html |title=Women's skeleton world championship medalists since 2000 (sports123.com)}}\n\n{{Footer World Cup Champions Skeleton Women}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hollingsworth, Mellisa}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Alberta]]\n[[Category:Canadian female skeleton racers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Canada]]\n[[Category:Olympic skeleton racers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Skeleton racers at the 2006 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Skeleton racers at the 2010 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in skeleton]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2006 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Skeleton racers at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Canada-Winter-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n{{Skeleton-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Mellisa Hollingsworth\n| image          = Mellisa Hollingsworth at OP 2010.jpg\n| image_size     = 220\n| caption        = Hollingsworth in Calgary (2010)\n| headercolor    = lightsteelblue\n| birth_date     = {{birth-date and age|October 4, 1980}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lacombe, Alberta]], Canada\n| website        = {{URL|http://www.melhollingsworth.ca|MelHollingsworth.ca}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|[[Skeleton (sport)|Skeleton]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{CAN}} }}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2006 Winter Olympics|2006 Turin]]|[[Skeleton at the 2006 Winter Olympics&nbsp;\u2013 Women's|Women]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBT World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIBT World Championships 2000|2000 Igls]]|Women}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIBT World Championships 2012|2012 Lake Placid]]|Women}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIBT World Championships 2011|2011 K\u00f6nigssee]]|Women}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIBT World Championships 2011|2011 K\u00f6nigssee]]|Mixed team}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIBT World Championships 2012|2012 Lake Placid]]|Mixed team}}\n}}\n\n'''Mellisa Hollingsworth''' (born October 4, 1980 in [[Lacombe, Alberta]]) is a retired [[Canadians|Canadian]] athlete who competed from 1995-2014. She won the bronze medal in the [[Skeleton at the 2006 Winter Olympics|women's skeleton event]] at the [[2006 Winter Olympics]] in [[Turin]].\n\nHollingsworth also won a silver in the women's skeleton event at the [[FIBT World Championships 2000|2000 FIBT World Championships]] in [[Igls]], [[Austria]]. She won the women's [[List of Skeleton World Cup champions|Skeleton World Cup]] overall title both in [[2005/2006 Skeleton World Cup|2005-6]] and in [[2009-10 Skeleton World Cup|2009\u201310]].\n\nHollingsworth is the cousin of [[Ryan Davenport]], who won three medals in the men's skeleton event at the [[FIBT World Championships]] in the late 1990s.\n\nHollingsworth participated in the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia. After three runs, she was in second position behind [[Amy Williams]] of Great Britain. However, in the final run, despite a personal best start time of 4.93 seconds, Hollingsworth fell behind and ended up finishing fifth overall.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Hollingsworth falls short of podium |url=http://www.ctvolympics.ca/skeleton/news/newsid=46861.html|publisher=CTV Olympics|date=2010-02-19|accessdate=2010-02-19|author=Jeff Blair and Allan Maki}}</ref>\n\nHollingsworth retired after participating in the [[2014 Winter Olympic Games]] in Sochi, Russia.  <ref>{{Cite web|title=Mellisa Hollingsworth begins her last medal mission |url=https://https://www.reddeeradvocate.com/news/mellisa-hollingsworth-begins-her-last-medal-mission/|publisher=Red-Deer-Advocate}</ref>\n\nIn summer 2018, Hollingsworth competed on ''[[The Amazing Race Canada 6|The Amazing Race Canada: Heroes Edition]]'' with barrel racer Nancy Csabay.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Barrel Racer Takes on The Amazing Race Canada |url=https://horse-canada.com/star-crossed-horses/barrel-racer-takes-on-the-amazing-race-canada/|publisher=Horse-Canada|date=2018-08-20|accessdate=2018-08-29}}</ref> They finished in 5th place.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Amazing Race Canada: Muertos and mercado in Mexico City |url=https://www.tv-eh.com/2018/08/28/amazing-race-canada-3-mexico-city/|publisher=TV, eh?|date=2018-08-28|accessdate=2018-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mellisa Hollingsworth}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.melhollingsworth.ca}}\n* {{COC profile|mellisa-hollingsworth}}\n* {{IOC profile|mellisa-hollingsworth}}\n* {{SR/Olympics profile|ho/mellisa-hollingsworth-richards-1|Mellisa Hollingsworth-Richards}}\n* {{IBSF|100564|Mellisa Hollingsworth}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20030509075908/http://www.davenportsleds.ca/phryanmh.htm Picture of Davenport and Hollingsworth (davenportsleds.ca)]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111105170232/http://sports123.com/ske/wwc.html |title=List of women's skeleton World Cup champions since 1997 (sports123.com)}}\n* [http://sports123.com/ske/wo.html Women's skeleton Olympic medalists since 2002 (sports123.com)]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304035143/http://sports123.com/ske/ww.html |title=Women's skeleton world championship medalists since 2000 (sports123.com)}}\n\n{{Footer World Cup Champions Skeleton Women}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hollingsworth, Mellisa}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Alberta]]\n[[Category:Canadian female skeleton racers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Canada]]\n[[Category:Olympic skeleton racers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Skeleton racers at the 2006 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Skeleton racers at the 2010 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in skeleton]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2006 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Skeleton racers at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Canada-Winter-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n{{Skeleton-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Template fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mellisa_Hollingsworth"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Duncombe (died 1779)", "text_new": "'''Thomas Duncombe''' (baptised 27 August 1724<ref>''England, Select Births and Christenings, 1538-1975''</ref> \u2013 23 November 1779) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] between 1751 and 1779.\n\n[[File:DuncombeParkJonesViews1829.jpg|thumb|[[Duncombe Park]], 1839]]\nDuncombe  was the eldest  son of [[Thomas Duncombe (died 1746)|Thomas Duncombe]], of [[Duncombe Park]], North Yorkshire and his wife, Mary Slingsby, daughter of Sir Thomas Slingsby.<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Debrett's Complete Peerage of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|author=Courthope, W.|date=1838|publisher=J. G. & F. Rivington|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Ru4UAAAAQAAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Ru4UAAAAQAAJ/page/n411 342]|accessdate=26 August 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Westminster School]] from an early age in 1732, and matriculated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]] on 18 May 1742, aged 17.<ref name=ALUM>{{alox2|title=Duncombe, Thomas}}</ref> He succeeded his father to [[Duncombe Park]] in 1746 and is also known as Thomas Duncombe III.\n\nIn 1751, Duncombe was returned  as [[Member of Parliament]] for the [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]] constituency. In [[1754 British general election|1754]] he was elected MP for [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]]. On the death of his cousin  [[Anthony Duncombe, 1st Baron Feversham|Lord Feversham]] in 1763 he inherited an interest at Downton, and in 1768 was returned to Parliament unopposed.  In 1774 his control of the Downton seat was challenged  and he was unseated on petition.  He was returned unopposed for Downton in 1779, but died a few weeks later on 23 November 1779. There is no record of his having spoken in Parliament.<ref name = HOP/>\n\n==Family==\nDuncombe married  firstly Lady Diana Howard daughter of [[Henry Howard, 4th Earl of Carlisle]]  on  9 February 1749.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/duncombe-thomas-1724-79  | title= DUNCOMBE, Thomas (?1724-79), of Duncombe Park, Yorks. and Barford Park, Wilts.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 20 August 2017}}</ref>\nHe married secondly Anne Jennings, daughter of [[Sir Philip Jennings-Clerke, 1st Baronet|Sir Philip Jennings Clerke, Bt]]  on 24 February 1772. He married thirdly  Charlotte Hale, daughter of William Hale of King's Walden, Hertfordshire on 25 June 1778. Duncombe's daughter Anne married [[Bobby Shafto|Robert Shafto]].\n\nHaving no sons, Duncombe's estates at Barford, near Downton and Duncombe Park devolved to his younger brother Charles Slingsby Duncombe and thence to [[Charles Duncombe, 1st Baron Feversham]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://archive.org/details/historycasescon01glengoog <!-- quote=The History of the Cases of Controverted Elections. --> History of the Cases of Controverted Elections: Which Were Tried and Determined During the First and Second Sessions of the Fourteenth Parliament of Great Britain, 15 & 16 Geo. III. Sylvester Douglas Baron Glenbervie L. Hansard, 1802 P207-239]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Henry Vane, 2nd Earl of Darlington|Colonel Henry Vane]]\n | before2 = [[George Procter]] \n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]]\n | years = 1751\u2013[[1754 British general election|1754]]\n | with  =  [[Henry Vane, 2nd Earl of Darlington|Colonel Henry Vane]]   1751-1753 \n| with2 = [[James Hayes (1715-1800)|James Hayes]]  1753-1754\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[James Hayes (1715-1800)|James Hayes]]\n | after2 = [[James Cope (UK politician)|James Cope]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Robert Ord]]\n | before2 = [[James Hamilton, 1st Earl of Clanbrassil (1719)|Viscount Limerick]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]]\n | years = [[1754 British general election|1754]]\u2013[[1768 British general election|1768]]\n | with  =  [[Robert Ord]]   1754-1755\n| with2 = [[Sir Matthew Fetherstonhaugh, 1st Baronet|Sir Matthew Fetherstonhaugh]]   1755-1761\n| with3=  [[John Stewart, 7th Earl of Galloway|Viscount Garlies]]   1761-1768\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Peter Beckford (hunter)|Peter Beckford]]\n | after2 = [[Sir Matthew Ridley, 2nd Baronet|Sir Matthew White Ridley]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Thomas Hales, 4th Baronet|Thomas Pym Hales]]\n | before2 = [[James Hayes (1715-1800)|James Hayes]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]]\n | years = [[1768 British general election|1768]]\u20131775\n | with  =  [[Richard Croftes]]     1768-1771\n | with2 = [[James Hayes (1715-1800)|James Hayes]]   1771-1774\n| with3=   [[Thomas Dummer]]   1774-1775\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[John Cooper (died 1779)|John Cooper]]\n | after2 = [[Sir Philip Hales, 5th Baronet|Sir Philip Hales]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Cooper (died 1779)|John Cooper]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Philip Hales, 5th Baronet|Sir Philip Hales]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]]\n | years = 1779\u20131779\n | with  =  [[Sir Philip Hales, 5th Baronet|Sir Philip Hales]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Bartholomew Bouverie]]\n | after2 = [[Sir Philip Hales, 5th Baronet|Sir Philip Hales]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duncombe, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1724 births]]\n[[Category:1779 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1754\u20131761]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1761\u20131768]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1768\u20131774]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n", "text_old": "'''Thomas Duncombe''' (baptised 27 August 1724<ref>''England, Select Births and Christenings, 1538-1975''</ref> \u2013 23 November 1779) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] between 1751 and 1779.\n\n[[File:DuncombeParkJonesViews1829.jpg|thumb|[[Duncombe Park]], 1839]]\nDuncombe  was the eldest  son of [[Thomas Duncombe (died 1746)|Thomas Duncombe]], of [[Duncombe Park]], North Yorkshire and his wife, Mary Slingsby, daughter of Sir Thomas Slingsby.<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Debrett's Complete Peerage of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|author=Courthope, W.|date=1838|publisher=J. G. & F. Rivington|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Ru4UAAAAQAAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Ru4UAAAAQAAJ/page/n411 342]|accessdate=26 August 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Westminster School]] from an early age in 1732, and matriculated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]] on 18 May 1742, aged 17.<ref name=ALUM>{{alox2|title=Duncombe, Thomas}}</ref> He succeeded his father to [[Duncombe Park]] in 1746 and is also known as Thomas Duncombe III.\n\nIn 1751, Duncombe was returned  as [[Member of Parliament]] for the [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]] constituency. In [[1754 British general election|1754]] he was elected MP for [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]]. On the death of his cousin  [[Anthony Duncombe, 1st Baron Feversham|Lord Feversham]] in 1763 he inherited an interest at Downton, and in 1768 was returned to Parliament unopposed.  In 1774 his control of the Downton seat was challenged  and he was unseated on petition.  He was returned unopposed for Downton in 1779, but died a few weeks later on 23 November 1779. There is no record of his having spoken in Parliament.<ref name = HOP/>\n\n==Family==\nDuncombe married  firstly Lady Diana Howard daughter of [[Henry Howard, 4th Earl of Carlisle]]  on  9 February 1749.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/duncombe-thomas-1724-79  | title= DUNCOMBE, Thomas (?1724-79), of Duncombe Park, Yorks. and Barford Park, Wilts.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 20 August 2017}}</ref>\nHe married secondly Anne Jennings, daughter of [[Sir Philip Jennings-Clerke, 1st Baronet|Sir Philip Jennings Clerke, Bt]]  on 24 February 1772. He married thirdly  Charlotte Hale, daughter of William Hale of King\u2019s Walden, Hertfordshire on 25 June 1778. Duncombe\u2019s daughter Anne married [[Bobby Shafto|Robert Shafto]].\n\nHaving no sons, Duncombe's estates at Barford, near Downton and Duncombe Park devolved to his younger brother Charles Slingsby Duncombe and thence to [[Charles Duncombe, 1st Baron Feversham]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://archive.org/details/historycasescon01glengoog <!-- quote=The History of the Cases of Controverted Elections. --> History of the Cases of Controverted Elections: Which Were Tried and Determined During the First and Second Sessions of the Fourteenth Parliament of Great Britain, 15 & 16 Geo. III. Sylvester Douglas Baron Glenbervie L. Hansard, 1802 P207-239]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Henry Vane, 2nd Earl of Darlington|Colonel Henry Vane]]\n | before2 = [[George Procter]] \n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]]\n | years = 1751\u2013[[1754 British general election|1754]]\n | with  =  [[Henry Vane, 2nd Earl of Darlington|Colonel Henry Vane]]   1751-1753 \n| with2 = [[James Hayes (1715-1800)|James Hayes]]  1753-1754\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[James Hayes (1715-1800)|James Hayes]]\n | after2 = [[James Cope (UK politician)|James Cope]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Robert Ord]]\n | before2 = [[James Hamilton, 1st Earl of Clanbrassil (1719)|Viscount Limerick]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]]\n | years = [[1754 British general election|1754]]\u2013[[1768 British general election|1768]]