076/bongbong-marcos-positive-for-covid-19/story/|publisher=[[GMA News Online]] |date=March 31, 2010}}</ref>\n:Tested along with wife Liza and entire staff with negative results in a single day according to wife's March 26, 2020 statement via [[The Philippine Star]],<ref name=\"philstarBongbongLiza\">{{cite news |title=Bongbong Marcos' family, staff take COVID-19 tests which turn out negative |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/26/2003570/bongbong-marcos-family-staff-take-covid-19-tests-which-turn-out-negative |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> but still awaited results.<ref name=\"gmaStatementBongbongWife\"/><ref name=\"absCbnBongbongMarcos\">{{cite news |last1=Torres |first1=Sherrie Ann |title='Unwell' Bongbong Marcos takes COVID-19 test: Imee |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/amp/news/03/26/20/bongbong-marcos-covid-19-coronavirus-test |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"rapplerTweetBongbong\">{{cite news |last1=Cepeda |first1=Mara |title=Ex-senator Bongbong Marcos: I am deeply touched and overwhelmed by your concern over my condition. |url=https://twitter.com/rapplerdotcom/status/1243049480489824256 |publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Ma. Angelica |title=Statement allegedly from Bongbong Marcos' wife says they got COVID-19 test results in a day |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731443/statement-allegedly-from-bongbong-marcos-wife-says-they-got-covid-19-test-results-in-a-day/story/ |publisher=[[GMA News Online]] |date=March 26, 2010}}</ref>\n:Noted to have a recent travel history to Spain.<ref name=\"philstarBongbongLiza\"/>\n* Former First Lady and [[Ilocos]] congresswoman and governor [[Imelda Marcos]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{Abbr|{{small|TBA}}|to be announced}}<ref name=\"No to VIP testing \" />\n* Former special envoy to China [[Ramon Tulfo]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"interaksyonOfficialsIssuingApologies\"/><ref name=\"twitterTulfo\">{{cite web |last1=Tulfo |first1=Ramon |title=I tested negative for Covid-19. |url=https://twitter.com/RamonTulfoII/status/1241573761389752320 |website=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020|date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"facebookTulfo\">{{cite web |last1=Tulfo |first1=Ramon |title=I tested negative for the deadly Covid-19. |url=https://www.facebook.com/isumbongmo.kaytulfo.56/posts/812617152582686 |website=[[Facebook]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Family members of Philippine government officials ====\nThe following is a list of individuals who were given COVID-19 testing at the same time as their relatives who were either government officials or former government officials.\n<!-- Kindly arrange entries alphabetically by the last name of their politician relative. -->\n\n===== Relatives of President Rodrigo Duterte =====\n* [[Honeylet Avance\u00f1a]] (common-law wife)&nbsp;\u2013 {{Abbr|{{small|TBA}}|to be announced}}<ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"manilaTimesDuterteFamily\" />\n:On March 17, according to Senator [[Bong Go|Go]], their swab tests were conducted in Davao City.<ref name=\"presidentialfamily\">{{cite web |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/duterte-family-tested-for-covid-19 |title=Duterte family tested for COVID-19 |last=Merez|first=Arianne|publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* Kitty Duterte (youngest daughter)&nbsp;\u2013 {{Abbr|{{small|TBA}}|to be announced}}<ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"manilaTimesDuterteFamily\" /><ref name=\"presidentialfamily\"/>\n\n===== Relatives and staff of Former Senator Bongbong Marcos =====\n* Liza Marcos (wife)&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"philstarBongbongLiza\">{{cite news |title=Bongbong Marcos' family, staff take COVID-19 tests which turn out negative |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/26/2003570/bongbong-marcos-family-staff-take-covid-19-tests-which-turn-out-negative |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gmaStatementBongbongWife\" /><ref name=\"rapplerTweetBongbong\">{{cite news |last1=Cepeda |first1=Mara |title=Ex-senator Bongbong Marcos: I am deeply touched and overwhelmed by your concern over my condition. |url=https://twitter.com/rapplerdotcom/status/1243049480489824256 |publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n* Staff members of the Bongbong and Liza Marcos \u2013 negative<ref name=\"philstarBongbongLiza\"/><ref name=\"gmaStatementBongbongWife\"/><ref name=\"rapplerTweetBongbong\"/>\n\n===== Relatives of Senator Miguel Zubiri =====\n* Audrey Tan (wife)&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"gmaZubiriWife\">{{cite news |last=Magsino|first=Dona|title=Zubiri's wife tests negative for COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730053/zubiri-s-wife-tests-negative-for-covid-19/story/ |date=March 17, 2020 |ref=[[GMA News Online]]}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\nThis bypassing of the testing protocol of supposed VIPs has resulted in public outcry, given the scarcity of COVID-19 testing kits available to the public. On March 22, 2020, the [[hashtag]]s \"#NoToVIPTesting\" and \"#CheckYourPrivilege\" trended on [[Twitter]], reflecting public anger on the issue.<ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\">{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Politicians and their families get tested for COVID-19, but some people are not having it |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/18/164524/politicians-families-get-tested-some-not-having/ |publisher=[[Interaksyon]] |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gmaDuqueRITM\">{{cite news |last1=Rita |first1=Joviland |title=Duque clarifies RITM director was not replaced amid alleged VIP testing for COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730851/duque-clarifies-ritm-director-was-not-replaced-amid-alleged-vip-testing-for-covid-19/story/ |publisher=[[GMA News Online]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"No to VIP testing \">{{Cite news |last=Robles |first=Alan |url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/3076788/coronavirus-philippines-leak-shows-politicians-and-relatives |title=Coronavirus: in Philippines, leak shows politicians and relatives received 'VIP' testing |date=March 25, 2020 |website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\nSome politicians issued apologies for getting tested, acknowledging that they \"may have skipped\" the protocols set by the DOH for determining which patients needed to get tested first.<ref name=\"interaksyonOfficialsIssuingApologies\">{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Officials issuing apologies for availing of COVID-19 testing kits |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/23/164799/officials-apologies-for-availing-of-covid-19-testing-kits/ |publisher=[[Interaksyon]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Philippines}}\n* [[COVID-19 testing]]\n* [[Dengvaxia controversy]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on politics]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.covid19.gov.ph/ Philippine Government's Online Portal for the COVID-19 Pandemic].\n* [https://www.doh.gov.ph/2019-nCoV Updates on Novel Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19)] by the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]], Situation tracker, updated daily.\n* [https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/ COVID-19 cases tracker by the Philippines' Department of Health]\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|Coronavirus testing controversy]]\n[[Category:Medical controversies]]\n[[Category:2020 controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=April 2020}}\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n<!---Undue weight to the list, as per AFD consensus. Consensus is to reframe the article to focus on the testing controversy itself. See talk page for discussion--->\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Undue weight|date=April 2020}}{{Cleanup|reason=Reframe the article to give more focus to the COVID-19 testing controversy itself rather than listing every tested public figure as per the [[Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/List of Philippine public figures who underwent COVID-19 testing|1st Articles for deletion]] discussion|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n\nThe '''coronavirus testing controversy''' is an ongoing controversy involving several government officials who were reported in media to have been [[COVID-19 testing|tested for coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the first months of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines\u200e]], supposedly bypassing the triage algorithm which was set up by the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] (DOH).  \n\nAt the time, the DOH had set up the triage algorithm as a way to maximize resources, given the scarcity of COVID-19 test kits and the limited number of laboratories capable of processing the test results.  In some instances, the controversy extended to family members of these government officials, which had also been given early COVID-19 testing despite the algorithm.\n\n== Background ==\n=== Scarcity of laboratories and test kits ===\n{{further|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\nThe Philippine government did not have the capacity to test for the [[SARS-CoV-2]] virus until January 30, 2020, when the government-run [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] (RITM) was finally able to run confirmatory tests. Until that date, samples from suspected COVID-19 cases had to be sent to Victorian Infectious Diseases Reference Laboratory in [[Melbourne]], Australia for testing.<ref name=\"phacquires\">{{cite news |title=PH acquires confirmatory test kits for novel coronavirus |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/29/Novel-coronavirus-confirmatory-test-kits-primers-RITM.html |publisher=CNN |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> \n\nHowever, there were still very few testing kits in the Philippines, and the RITM was still the only laboratory that had the ability to process test results. By March 9, 2020, only 200 to 250 tests could be processed per day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magtulis |first1=Prinz |title=With only 250 people tested a day, Philippine health sector appears ill-prepared for COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/09/1999444/only-250-people-tested-day-philippine-health-sector-appears-ill-prepared-covid-19 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nBy March 23, 2020 the number had gone up to almost 1000 a day, as new laboratories gained the capacity to process test results and various entities donated about 100,000 test kits to the RITM.  But the Philippines' overall capacity to do COVID-19 testing was still very limited given the national spread of the disease.<ref name=\"dohsends100k\">{{cite news |title=DOH sends 100,000 test kits to RITM, testing centers nationwide |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/23/Coronavirus-Philippines-test-kits-testing-centers.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, 2020, the Philippines' national government began \"progressive mass testing\" for COVID-19<ref name=\"CNNProgressiveMassTesting\">{{Cite web |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/14/Philippines-COVID-19-mass-testing.html |title=PH begins 'progressive' COVID-19 mass testing |website=cnn |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414052020/https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/14/Philippines-COVID-19-mass-testing.html |archive-date=2020-04-14 |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> after it received \"tens of thousands of testing kits\" from  various donor countries,<ref name=\"BidabidangSG\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/virus-deaths-spike-ahead-of-mass-testing-in-philippines |title=Coronavirus deaths spike ahead of mass testing in Philippines |last=Dancel |first=Raul |date=2020-04-13 |website=The Straits Times |language=en |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and SARS-COV-2 test kits produced by the [[University of the Philippines]]' Philippine Genome Center became available.<ref name=\"RhiaUPTestKits\">{{Cite web |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/03/14/20/meet-the-filipino-scientist-who-invented-the-low-cost-covid-19-testing-kits |title=Meet the Filipino scientist who invented the low-cost COVID-19 testing kits |last=Diomampo-Grana |first=Rhia |website=ABS-CBN News |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>  To process these tests, the DOH reported that \"dozens of testing laboratories\" would come online within the month.<ref name=\"BidabidangSG\">\n\n=== Philippine triage decision algorithm ===\nAs soon as the government gained the ability to conduct COVID-19 tests locally, they developed a [[triage]] algorithm which would serve as a \"decision tool.\" This would determine which patients would be allowed to use the few available test kits, and the processing time of the few Philippine laboratories capable of doing COVID-19 tests.<ref name=\"AlgorithmAO20200130\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/sites/default/files/health-update/COVID-19-Advisory-No2.pdf |title=Decision Tool for Novel Coronavirus Assessment for Bureau of Quarantine and Hospitals (Version as of January 30, 2020) |date=January 30, 2020 |website=Government of the Philippines Department of Health}}</ref>\n\nThe algorithm sorted people into \"[[Patient Under Investigation|patients under investigation]]\" (PUI), who would be given tests; and \"persons under monitoring\" (PUM), who would not be tested, but rather told to go into a 14-day self quarantine.<ref name=\"AlgorithmAO20200130\"/>\n\n== Prioritized testing of government officials ==\n{{see also|Cacique Democracy}}\nWhile some VIPs were legitimately on the priority list for testing, some of them who were not PUIs did not follow the [[medical guideline|medical protocol]] outlined by [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]]'s [[triage|triage algorithm]] and were tested ahead of the [[symptomatic]] people who were in the priority list, hence the [[Very important person|VIP]] treatment controversy.<ref name=\"DOHTriageAlgorithm\">{{cite web |title=Algorithm for Triage of Patients with Possible COVID-19 Infection in Healthcare Facilities |url=https://www.facebook.com/OfficialDOHgov/photos/a.157979910879936/3135067276504503/?type=3&theater |website=[[Facebook]] |publisher=[[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] |accessdate=March 23, 2020|date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"interaksyonDOHTriageSystem\">{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=A closer look at DOH's triage system and why politicians, officials are getting tested for COVID-19 |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/19/164632/closer-look-at-dohs-triage-system-and-why-politicians-are-getting-tested-for-covid-19/ |publisher=[[Interaksyon]] |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/27/20/makati-village-urges-pacquiao-family-to-self-quarantine-senator-says-will-always-follow-the-law |title=Makati village urges Pacquiao, family to self-quarantine; senator says 'will always follow the law'|date=March 27, 2020 |publisher=ABS-CBN News}}</ref><ref name=\"covid19confusioninPH\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/in-depth/255403-agonizing-confusion-coronavirus-testing-philippines |title=Hell on Earth: The agonizing confusion over coronavirus testing in PH |last=Cepeda |first=Mara |date=March 22, 2020 |website=Rappler.com}}</ref> This included family members and the staff of current and former government officials.<ref name=\"philstarBongbongLiza\">{{cite news |title=Bongbong Marcos' family, staff take COVID-19 tests which turn out negative |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/26/2003570/bongbong-marcos-family-staff-take-covid-19-tests-which-turn-out-negative |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gmaStatementBongbongWife\">{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Ma. Angelica |title=Statement allegedly from Bongbong Marcos' wife says they got COVID-19 test results in a day |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731443/statement-allegedly-from-bongbong-marcos-wife-says-they-got-covid-19-test-results-in-a-day/story/ |publisher=[[GMA News Online]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe DOH later issued a statement saying that these tests were a \"courtesy\" rather than a \"VIP treatment\" saying that \"there is no policy for VIP treatment and that all specimens are being processed on a first-in, first-out basis with courtesy accorded to officials holding positions of national security and public health.\"<ref name=\"LaraTanCourtesyTesting\">{{Cite news |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/23/Senator-Tito-Sotto-coronavirus-COVID-19-test.html |title=Health Dept. gives COVID-19 testing 'courtesy' to officials involved in nat'l security, public health |date=March 29, 2020|publisher=CNN Philippines|last=Tan|first=Lara}}</ref>\n\n== List of government officials who underwent COVID-19 testing ==\n{{Prose|date=April 2020}}\nThe following is a list of Philippine public figures, along with their immediate family members and staff, who were [[COVID-19 testing|tested]] for the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] and publicly disclosed it.\n\n<!-- Kindly arrange entries alphabetically by last name -->\n=== Executive ===\n==== National government ====\n* President [[Rodrigo Duterte]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"interaksyonDOHTriageSystem\" /><ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"gmaDuterteGoNoCovid\">{{cite news |last1=Cordero |first1=Ted |title=Duterte, Go have no COVID-19 infection, tests show |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729606/duterte-go-have-no-covid-19-infection-tests-show/story/ |publisher=[[GMA News Online]] |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"philstarZubiriPositive\" /><ref name=\"manilaTimesDuterteFamily\">{{cite news |last1=Valente |first1=Catherine S. |title=Duterte family undergoes Covid-19 test |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/17/news/latest-stories/duterte-family-undergoes-covid-19-test/703891/ |publisher=[[The Manila Times]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* Executive Secretary [[Salvador Medialdea]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"PalaceStatementOfficialsNegative\">{{cite news |last1=Geducos  |first1=Argyll Cyrus |title=Palace: Medialdea, Durante, other gov\u2019t officials test negative for COVID-19 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/22/baste-duterte-tests-negative-for-covid-19/ |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* Interior and Local Government Secretary Eduardo A\u00f1o&nbsp;\u2013 positive<ref>{{cite web |last=Fermin|first=Margret|title=Cesar Virata, martial law prime minister infected with COVID-19|date=April 1, 2020|url=https://philippineslifestyle.com/cesar-virata-martial-law-prime-minister-infected-with-covid-19/ |publisher=Philippine Lifestyle News}}</ref>\n* Budget Secretary [[Wendel Avisado]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"gmaNoHouseMember\">{{cite news |title=Cayetano: No House member under self-quarantine exhibiting symptoms of COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729884/cayetano-no-house-member-under-self-quarantine-exhibiting-symptoms-of-covid-19/story/ |date=March 16, 2020 |ref=[[GMA News Online]]}}</ref>\n* Transportation Secretary [[Arthur Tugade]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"gmaNoHouseMember\" />\n* Finance Secretary [[Carlos Dominguez]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"PalaceStatementOfficialsNegative\"/>\n* Public Works Secretary [[Mark Villar]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"PalaceStatementOfficialsNegative\"/>\n\n==== Governors ====\n* [[Jonvic Remulla]] ([[Cavite]])&nbsp;\u2013 {{small|TBA}}<ref name=\"No to VIP testing \" /><ref name=\"interaksyonOfficialsIssuingApologies\"/><ref name=\"yahooRemulla\">{{cite news |title=Asymptomatic Cavite Governor says sorry for taking COVID-19 test amid shortage |url=https://ph.news.yahoo.com/asymptomatic-cavite-governor-says-sorry-065444465.html |agency=Coconuts Manila |publisher=[[Yahoo News]] |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n:Asymptomatic, acknowledged bypassing the DOH's protocol and triage testing algorithm, apologized to public.\n\n==== Mayors ====\n* [[Leopoldo Bataoil]] ([[Lingayen]], [[Pangasinan]])&nbsp;\u2013 negative. Had persistent cough and was exposed to the Filipina who tested positive in Australia.<ref name=\"absCbnLingayen\">{{cite news |title=Lingayen mayor tests negative for coronavirus |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/10/20/lingayen-mayor-tests-negative-for-coronavirus |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Philip Crispino]] ([[Caba, La Union]])&nbsp;\u2013 positive<ref name=\"absCbnLaUnion\">{{cite news |last1=Ilao |first1=Micaella |title=La Union town mayor, councilor positive for COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/21/20/la-union-town-mayor-councilor-positive-for-covid-19 |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* Ferdie Estrella ([[Baliuag, Bulacan]])&nbsp;\u2013 positive<ref name=\"inqBulacanMayor\">{{cite news |last1=Galvez |first1=Daphne |title=Bulacan mayor tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243666/bulacan-mayor-tests-positive-for-covid-19 |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* Joric Garula ([[Taytay, Rizal]]) \u2013 positive<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/29/Taytay-Mayor-Joric-Gacula-tests-positive-COVID-19.html|title=Taytay, Rizal mayor tests positive for COVID-19|date=March 29, 2020|work=CNN Philippines|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Isko Moreno]] ([[Manila City]])&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"absCbnIsko\">{{cite news |title=Manila Mayor Isko Moreno tests negative for COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/15/20/manila-mayor-isko-moreno-tests-negative-for-covid-19 |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"philstarIsko\">{{cite news |last1=Galupo |first1=Rey |title=Isko undergoes testing for coronavirus |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/13/2000326/isko-undergoes-testing-coronavirus |publisher=[[Philippine Star]] |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n:* Cesar Chavez (Moreno's chief of staff), other city hall officials who accompanied mayor during trip to [[London]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{small|TBA}}<ref name=\"philstarIsko\" />\n\n==== Vice mayors ====\n* [[Sebastian Duterte]] ([[Davao City]])&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"manilaTimesDuterteFamily\" /><ref name=\"mbBaste\">{{cite news |last1=Colina IV |first1=Antonio |title='Baste' Duterte tests negative for COVID-19 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/22/baste-duterte-tests-negative-for-covid-19/ |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"presidentialfamily\"/>\n\n=== Legislative ===\n==== Senate ====\nThe Senate held a hearing concerning the Committee on Basic Education, Arts and Culture on March 5, 2020 where a resource person later tested positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"interaksyonDOHTriageSystem\"/>\n*[[Nancy Binay]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"interaksyonDOHTriageSystem\" /><ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"interaksyonOfficialsIssuingApologies\"/><ref name=\"yahooRemulla\" /><ref name=\"absCbnBinayGatchalian\">{{cite news |last1=Domingo |first1=Katrina |title=Binay, Gatchalian test negative for coronavirus |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/gatchalian-tests-negative-for-covid-19 |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Pia Cayetano]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{small|TBA}}<ref name=\"philstarTolentino\" /><ref name=\"mbSixMoreSenators\">{{cite news |last1=Terrazola |first1=Vanne Elaine |title=Six more senators undergo COVID-19 test |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/six-more-senators-undergo-covid-19-test/ |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Franklin Drilon]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative. Wife also negative.<ref name=\"mbSixMoreSenators\" />\n* [[Sherwin Gatchalian]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"interaksyonDOHTriageSystem\" /><ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"interaksyonOfficialsIssuingApologies\"/><ref name=\"yahooRemulla\" /><ref name=\"absCbnBinayGatchalian\" />\n* [[Bong Go]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"gmaDuterteGoNoCovid\" /><ref name=\"philstarZubiriPositive\" /><ref name=\"BongGo\">{{Cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/26/20/go-to-self-quarantine-after-exposure-to-coronavirus-infected-congressman |title=Go to self-quarantine after exposure to coronavirus-infected congressman |date=March 26, 2020 }}</ref>\n* [[Richard J. Gordon|Dick Gordon]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{small|TBA}}<ref name=\"mbSixMoreSenators\" />\n* [[Panfilo Lacson]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"philstarTolentino\" /><ref name=\"mbSixMoreSenators\" /><ref name=\"dzbbLacsonandSotto\">{{cite news |last1=de la Pe\u00f1a |first1=Weng |title=LIVESTREAM: Dobol B sa News TV Livestream: March 22, 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c9l7Cnaeo9I&t=8480 |publisher=[[DZBB-AM]] |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Imee Marcos]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{small|TBA}}<ref name=\"philstarTolentino\" /><ref name=\"mbSixMoreSenators\" />\n* [[Manny Pacquiao]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative <ref name=\"Pacquiao\" >{{cite web |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/28/20/pacquiao-tests-negative-coronavirus |title=Quarantined Pacquiao says negative for coronavirus after rapid test |date=March 28, 2020 |publisher=ABS-CBN News}}</ref>\n:He said he received a rapid testing kit from friends from South Korea, though not approved by the Food and Drug Administration.\n* [[Grace Poe]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{small|TBA}}<ref name=\"philstarTolentino\" /><ref name=\"mbSixMoreSenators\" />\n* [[Bong Revilla]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{small|TBA}}<ref name=\"philstarTolentino\" /><ref name=\"mbSixMoreSenators\" />\n* [[Tito Sotto]]&nbsp;\u2013 tested twice. 1st test negative. 2nd test {{small|TBA}}<ref name=\"philstarTolentino\" /><ref name=\"mbSixMoreSenators\" /><ref name=\"dzbbLacsonandSotto\" />\n: Sotto said that the first test was made using a kit not accredited by the DOH. He subsequently took a second test, this time using a DOH-accredited kit after he began exhibitng dry cough and sore throat.<ref name=\"vipsenatorclarify\">{{cite news |last1=Tan |first1=Lara |title=VIP treatment? Senators clarify their use of COVID-19 test kits amid backlash |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/23/Senator-Tito-Sotto-coronavirus-COVID-19-test.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Stated that he was willing to take a 3rd test after exposure to Rep. Eric Go Yap.<ref name=\"absCbnTitoSottoAnotherTest\">{{cite news |title=Sotto willing to take another COVID-19 test after exposure to Rep. Yap |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/26/20/sotto-willing-to-take-another-covid-19-test-after-exposure-to-rep-yap |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Francis Tolentino]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"interaksyonOfficialsIssuingApologies\"/><ref name=\"philstarTolentino\">{{Cite news |last=Luna |first=Franco |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322120108/http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/22/2002723/tolentino-tests-negative-covid-19-despite-doh-guideline-not-test-if-asymptomatic|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/22/2002723/tolentino-tests-negative-covid-19-despite-doh-guideline-not-test-if-asymptomatic |title=Tolentino tests negative for COVID-19 despite DOH guideline not to test if asymptomatic |archive-date=March 22, 2020 |publisher=[[Philippine Star]] |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"mbSixMoreSenators\" />\n:Said that his testing kit did not come from the DOH. Took the test believing he has been exposed to a person who tested positive for COVID-19 and began exhibiting symptoms.<ref name=\"No to VIP testing \" /><ref name=\"vipsenatorclarify\"/>\n* [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]]&nbsp;\u2013 positive<ref name=\"interaksyonDOHTriageSystem\" /><ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\"/><ref name=\"philstarZubiriPositive\">{{cite news |last1=Cabico |first1=Gaea Katreena |title=Migz Zubiri tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/16/2001414/migz-zubiri-tests-positive-covid-19 |publisher=[[Philippine Star]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"inqBulacanMayor\" />\n: The first national-level elected official to test positive in the Philippines. Tested despite being asymptomatic. Suspected to be a [[false positive]] by Health Secretary Duque who would have Zubiri tested again if not for the limited stock of testing kits.\n\n==== House of Representatives ====\n* [[Paolo Duterte]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{Abbr|{{small|TBA}}|to be announced}}<ref name=\"manilaTimesDuterteFamily\" /><ref name=\"presidentialfamily\"/>\n* [[Eric Go Yap]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256135-ritm-says-congressman-eric-yap-remains-negative-coronavirus-covid-19|title='Clerical oversight': RITM says congressman Yap 'remains negative' for COVID-19|publisher=Rappler|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"RITM_Yap\">{{cite web |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1249618/ritm-says-lawmaker-initially-positive-for-covid-19-doesnt-have-virus|title=RITM says Rep. Yap negative for COVID-19, admits 'clerical oversight'|publisher=The Philippine Daily Inquirer|last=Lalu|first=Gabriel Pabico|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/27/20/rep-yap-negative-for-covid-19-ritm-clarifies-apologizes-for-clerical-oversight|title=Rep. Yap negative for COVID-19, RITM clarifies; apologizes for 'clerical oversight'|publisher=ABS-CBN News|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/27/eric-yap-covid-19-diagnosis-ritm.html|title=Rep. Yap doesn't have COVID-19; RITM apologizes for 'oversight'|publisher=CNN Philippines|last=Santos|first=Elmor|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/27/2003844/rep-eric-go-yap-negative-covid-19-ritm-apologizes-mistake|title=Rep. Eric Go Yap negative for COVID-19; RITM apologizes for mistake|publisher=The Philippine Star|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731592/ritm-says-yap-negative-for-covid-19-apologizes-for-error/story/|title=RITM says Yap negative for COVID-19, apologizes for error|publisher=GMA News|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n:On March 27, the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine|RITM]] reached out and apologized to Yap, informing him that he actually tested negative and correcting the initial positive result as brought by an \"encoding error\".<ref name=\"RITM_Yap\"/>\n\n=== Judiciary ===\n==== Supreme Court ====\n* Chief Justice [[Diosdado Peralta]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"scCJPeralta\">{{cite web |title=CJ Peralta Tests Negative of COVID-19 |url=http://sc.judiciary.gov.ph/11058/ |website=Supreme Court of the Philippines |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n:Had history of travelling to the [[Netherlands]] in early March 2020 and exhibited symptoms.\n\n==== Former government officials ====\n*Former Senator [[Bongbong Marcos]]&nbsp;\u2013 positive <ref>{{cite web|last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Bongbong Marcos positive for COVID-19|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/732076/bongbong-marcos-positive-for-covid-19/story/|publisher=[[GMA News Online]] |date=March 31, 2010}}</ref>\n:Tested along with wife Liza and entire staff with negative results in a single day according to wife's March 26, 2020 statement via [[The Philippine Star]],<ref name=\"philstarBongbongLiza\">{{cite news |title=Bongbong Marcos' family, staff take COVID-19 tests which turn out negative |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/26/2003570/bongbong-marcos-family-staff-take-covid-19-tests-which-turn-out-negative |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> but still awaited results.<ref name=\"gmaStatementBongbongWife\"/><ref name=\"absCbnBongbongMarcos\">{{cite news |last1=Torres |first1=Sherrie Ann |title='Unwell' Bongbong Marcos takes COVID-19 test: Imee |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/amp/news/03/26/20/bongbong-marcos-covid-19-coronavirus-test |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"rapplerTweetBongbong\">{{cite news |last1=Cepeda |first1=Mara |title=Ex-senator Bongbong Marcos: I am deeply touched and overwhelmed by your concern over my condition. |url=https://twitter.com/rapplerdotcom/status/1243049480489824256 |publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Ma. Angelica |title=Statement allegedly from Bongbong Marcos' wife says they got COVID-19 test results in a day |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731443/statement-allegedly-from-bongbong-marcos-wife-says-they-got-covid-19-test-results-in-a-day/story/ |publisher=[[GMA News Online]] |date=March 26, 2010}}</ref>\n:Noted to have a recent travel history to Spain.<ref name=\"philstarBongbongLiza\"/>\n* Former First Lady and [[Ilocos]] congresswoman and governor [[Imelda Marcos]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{Abbr|{{small|TBA}}|to be announced}}<ref name=\"No to VIP testing \" />\n* Former special envoy to China [[Ramon Tulfo]]&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"interaksyonOfficialsIssuingApologies\"/><ref name=\"twitterTulfo\">{{cite web |last1=Tulfo |first1=Ramon |title=I tested negative for Covid-19. |url=https://twitter.com/RamonTulfoII/status/1241573761389752320 |website=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020|date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"facebookTulfo\">{{cite web |last1=Tulfo |first1=Ramon |title=I tested negative for the deadly Covid-19. |url=https://www.facebook.com/isumbongmo.kaytulfo.56/posts/812617152582686 |website=[[Facebook]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Family members of Philippine government officials ====\nThe following is a list of individuals who were given COVID-19 testing at the same time as their relatives who were either government officials or former government officials.\n<!-- Kindly arrange entries alphabetically by the last name of their politician relative. -->\n\n===== Relatives of President Rodrigo Duterte =====\n* [[Honeylet Avance\u00f1a]] (common-law wife)&nbsp;\u2013 {{Abbr|{{small|TBA}}|to be announced}}<ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"manilaTimesDuterteFamily\" />\n:On March 17, according to Senator [[Bong Go|Go]], their swab tests were conducted in Davao City.<ref name=\"presidentialfamily\">{{cite web |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/duterte-family-tested-for-covid-19 |title=Duterte family tested for COVID-19 |last=Merez|first=Arianne|publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* Kitty Duterte (youngest daughter)&nbsp;\u2013 {{Abbr|{{small|TBA}}|to be announced}}<ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"manilaTimesDuterteFamily\" /><ref name=\"presidentialfamily\"/>\n\n===== Relatives and staff of Former Senator Bongbong Marcos =====\n* Liza Marcos (wife)&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"philstarBongbongLiza\">{{cite news |title=Bongbong Marcos' family, staff take COVID-19 tests which turn out negative |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/26/2003570/bongbong-marcos-family-staff-take-covid-19-tests-which-turn-out-negative |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gmaStatementBongbongWife\" /><ref name=\"rapplerTweetBongbong\">{{cite news |last1=Cepeda |first1=Mara |title=Ex-senator Bongbong Marcos: I am deeply touched and overwhelmed by your concern over my condition. |url=https://twitter.com/rapplerdotcom/status/1243049480489824256 |publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n* Staff members of the Bongbong and Liza Marcos \u2013 negative<ref name=\"philstarBongbongLiza\"/><ref name=\"gmaStatementBongbongWife\"/><ref name=\"rapplerTweetBongbong\"/>\n\n===== Relatives of Senator Miguel Zubiri =====\n* Audrey Tan (wife)&nbsp;\u2013 negative<ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\" /><ref name=\"gmaZubiriWife\">{{cite news |last=Magsino|first=Dona|title=Zubiri's wife tests negative for COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730053/zubiri-s-wife-tests-negative-for-covid-19/story/ |date=March 17, 2020 |ref=[[GMA News Online]]}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\nThis bypassing of the testing protocol of supposed VIPs has resulted in public outcry, given the scarcity of COVID-19 testing kits available to the public. On March 22, 2020, the [[hashtag]]s \"#NoToVIPTesting\" and \"#CheckYourPrivilege\" trended on [[Twitter]], reflecting public anger on the issue.<ref name=\"interaksyonPoliticiansFamilies\">{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Politicians and their families get tested for COVID-19, but some people are not having it |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/18/164524/politicians-families-get-tested-some-not-having/ |publisher=[[Interaksyon]] |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gmaDuqueRITM\">{{cite news |last1=Rita |first1=Joviland |title=Duque clarifies RITM director was not replaced amid alleged VIP testing for COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730851/duque-clarifies-ritm-director-was-not-replaced-amid-alleged-vip-testing-for-covid-19/story/ |publisher=[[GMA News Online]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"No to VIP testing \">{{Cite news |last=Robles |first=Alan |url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/3076788/coronavirus-philippines-leak-shows-politicians-and-relatives |title=Coronavirus: in Philippines, leak shows politicians and relatives received 'VIP' testing |date=March 25, 2020 |website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\nSome politicians issued apologies for getting tested, acknowledging that they \"may have skipped\" the protocols set by the DOH for determining which patients needed to get tested first.<ref name=\"interaksyonOfficialsIssuingApologies\">{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Officials issuing apologies for availing of COVID-19 testing kits |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/23/164799/officials-apologies-for-availing-of-covid-19-testing-kits/ |publisher=[[Interaksyon]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Philippines}}\n* [[COVID-19 testing]]\n* [[Dengvaxia controversy]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on politics]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.covid19.gov.ph/ Philippine Government's Online Portal for the COVID-19 Pandemic].\n* [https://www.doh.gov.ph/2019-nCoV Updates on Novel Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19)] by the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]], Situation tracker, updated daily.\n* [https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/ COVID-19 cases tracker by the Philippines' Department of Health]\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|Coronavirus testing controversy]]\n[[Category:Medical controversies]]\n[[Category:2020 controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Chieharumachi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eScarcity of laboratories and test kits:corrected reference typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Philippine_coronavirus_testing_controversy"}
{"title_page": "Lithgow Small Arms Factory", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Lithgow Arms\n| logo = Lithgow Small Arms Factory logo.png\n| logo_size = 200px\n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| former_name = \n| type = \n| industry = [[Firearms]], [[Arms industry|Defence]]\n| genre = \n| fate = \n| successor = \n| founded = {{start date and age|1912|6|8}}\n| founder = \n| defunct = \n| hq_location_city = [[Lithgow, New South Wales|Lithgow]], [[New South Wales]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Australia]]\n| area_served = worldwide\n| key_people = \n| products = [[Pistol]]s, [[Rifle]]s, [[Carbine]]s, [[Submachine gun]]s, [[Machine gun]]s\n| revenue =  \n| revenue_year = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = \n| parent = [[Thales Australia]]\n| homepage = [http://www.lithgowarms.com www.lithgowarms.com]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n{{coord|-33.4875718|150.1397288|display=title}}\nThe '''Lithgow Small Arms Factory''', or '''Lithgow Arms''', is an [[Australia]]n [[small arms]] manufacturing factory located in the town of [[Lithgow, New South Wales]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:SLNSW 796565 Small Arms Factory Lithgow.jpg|thumb|Lithgow Small Arms Factory in 1910s~1920s]]\nOpened on 8 June 1912, the factory initially manufactured [[Lee-Enfield#Short Magazine Lee-Enfield Mk III|SMLE III]] rifles (and [[Pattern 1907 bayonet]]s) for the Australian military during [[World War I]].<ref name=lsmamuseum>{{cite web|url=http://lithgowsafmuseum.org.au/history.html|title=History and production|work=Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum|accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref>  During [[World War II]], production expanded to include [[Vickers machine gun]]s, [[Bren gun]]s and, postwar, branched out into sporting goods (including civilian firearms and [[Golf club (equipment)|golf club]]s), tools, [[sewing machines]], (from the mid-1950s) the [[F1 submachine gun]], [[L1A1 Self Loading Rifle|L1A1 SLR]], [[KAL1 general purpose infantry rifle]] [[prototype]]s and similar products.\n\nThe Lithgow Small Arms Factory was known to produce their [[single shot]] models 1A and 1B as well as their Model 12 [[repeating rifle|repeater]] under the [[Slazenger]] brand during the 1960s.<ref name=lsmamuseum/>  The factory was first \"corporatised\" as Australian Defence Industries by the [[Hawke Government]], then later sold in 2006.  ADI Lithgow is now owned by [[Thales Australia]] and continues to manufacture the [[F88 Austeyr]] rifle and [[FN Minimi|F89 Minimi]] currently used by the [[Australian military]].<ref name=lsmamuseum/>  \n\nAs a separate entity, not owned or run by the current owners of the factory, the volunteer-run Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum is located at the front of the disused section of site and has a large collection of military and civilian firearms manufactured at the factory and elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lithgowsafmuseum.org.au/index.html|title=Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum|accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref> In 2019, the museum was placed on the UNESCO Australian Memory of the World Register which lists influential collections and documents considered key to [[History of Australia|Australia's history]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lithgowmercury.com.au/story/5876115/small-arms-factory-recognised-in-unesco-world-register/|title=Small Arms Factory recognised in UNESCO World Register|last=Bastow|first=Ciara|date=2019-01-30|website=Lithgow Mercury|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> The museum sees 9,000 annual visitors and is a big draw to the city of Lithgow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lithgowmercury.com.au/story/6030095/lithgow-small-arms-museum-collection-put-at-risk-with-new-regulation-video/|title=Lithgow Small Arms Museum collection put at risk with new regulation {{!}} Video|last=Bastow|first=Ciara|date=2019-04-11|website=Lithgow Mercury|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\n\n=== Military ===\n\nAlongside the weapons listed below, the factory also produced bayonets, components, barrels, and magazines as well as repairing, modifying, and rechambering weapons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lithgowsafmuseum.org.au/milproduction.html|title=Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum|website=lithgowsafmuseum.org.au|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n* [[Lee\u2013Enfield|Short Magazine Lee Enfield]], some 50,000 rifles produced with variants including Mk III and Mk IV from 1912 to 1945.\n* [[Vickers machine gun]], 12,500 Mk I, Mk V, and Mk XXI produced from 1929 to 1943.\n* [[Bren light machine gun]], 17,500 produced from 1940 to 1945.\n* [[L1A1 Self Loading Rifle]], 222,773 rifles produced from 1959 to 1986\n* [[L2A1]], 9,557 produced\n* [[L1A1-F1]], 460 produced\n* [[F1 submachine gun]], 25,000 produced from 1962 to 1973\n* [[Austeyr F88]], produced from 1988\n* [[FN Minimi|Minimi F89]], produced from 1989\n\n=== Commercial ===\n\nA broad variety of weapons complemented the factory's military production, but also civilian products such as aircraft parts, golf heads, and tractor components, amongst other things.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lithgowsafmuseum.org.au/comproduction.html|title=Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum|website=lithgowsafmuseum.org.au|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n'''Discontinued firearms:'''\n* Lithgow Model 1 [[.22 caliber|.22]] [[single-shot]] rifle produced from 1945\n* Lithgow Model 1A .22 single-shot rifle\n* Lithgow Model 1B .22 single-shot rifle\n* Lithgow Model 12 .22 [[bolt-action]] 5-shot [[repeating rifle|repeater]] produced from 1947\n* Lithgow Model 12 .22 bolt-action 10-shot repeater (Bibby)\n* Lithgow Model 24 [[.22 Hornet]] cartridge produced from 1949\n* A single shot bolt action shotgun using the [[.410 bore|.410\" cartridge]] (name unknown)\n\n'''Current production firearms:'''\n* Lithgow LA101 CrossOver [[bolt-action]] [[Rimfire ammunition|rimfire]] rifle, available in [[.17 HMR]], [[.22 LR]] and [[.22 WMR]]\n* Lithgow LA102 CrossOver bolt-action [[centerfire]] rifle, available in [[.223 Rem]], [[.243 Win]] and [[.308 Win]]\n* Lithgow LA105 Woomera bolt-action centerfire rifle available, in [[6.5mm Creedmoor]] and .308 Win\n* [[F90 assault rifle|Lithgow F90 Semi Auto/Automatic Military Grade Rifle]], available in [[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lithgowarms.com/f90/|title=F90 Automatic Rifle Family \u2013 Lithgow Arms|website=www.lithgowarms.com|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref>\n** Lithgow F90MBR Modular Bullpup Rifle, available in 5.56\u00d745mm NATO\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Griffiths|first=Tony|title=Lithgow's Small Arms Factory and its People|volume=2 volumes|year=2006|publisher=Toptech Engineering|location=Terrey Hills, New South Wales|isbn=9780975064610}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.lithgowarms.com}}\n* [http://www.lithgowsafmuseum.org.au Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum Website (not affiliated with Lithgow Arms or Thales)]\n* [http://www.lithgow-tourism.com/smallarms.htm Lithgow Tourism]\n* [http://www.thalesgroup.com/Countries/Australia/Home/ Thales Australia]\n\n[[Category:Military installations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Museums in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Military and war museums in Australia]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Military installations established in 1912]]\n[[Category:Military history of New South Wales]]\n\n\n{{NewSouthWales-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Lithgow Arms\n| logo = Lithgow Small Arms Factory logo.png\n| logo_size = 200px\n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| former_name = \n| type = \n| industry = [[Firearms]], [[Arms industry|Defence]]\n| genre = \n| fate = \n| successor = \n| founded = {{start date and age|1912|6|8}}\n| founder = \n| defunct = \n| hq_location_city = [[Lithgow, New South Wales|Lithgow]], [[New South Wales]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Australia]]\n| area_served = worldwide\n| key_people = \n| products = [[Pistol]]s, [[Rifle]]s, [[Carbine]]s, [[Submachine gun]]s, [[Machine gun]]s\n| revenue =  \n| revenue_year = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = \n| parent = [[Thales Australia]]\n| homepage = [http://www.lithgowarms.com www.lithgowarms.com]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n{{coord|-33.4875718|150.1397288|display=title}}\nThe '''Lithgow Small Arms Factory''', or '''Lithgow Arms''', is an [[Australia]]n [[small arms]] manufacturing factory located in the town of [[Lithgow, New South Wales]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:SLNSW 796565 Small Arms Factory Lithgow.jpg|thumb|Lithgow Small Arms Factory in 1910s~1920s]]\nOpened on 8 June 1912, the factory initially manufactured [[Lee-Enfield#Short Magazine Lee-Enfield Mk III|SMLE III]] rifles (and [[Pattern 1907 bayonet]]s) for the Australian military during [[World War I]].<ref name=lsmamuseum>{{cite web|url=http://lithgowsafmuseum.org.au/history.html|title=History and production|work=Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum|accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref>  During [[World War II]], production expanded to include [[Vickers machine gun]]s, [[Bren gun]]s and, postwar, branched out into sporting goods (including civilian firearms and [[Golf club (equipment)|golf club]]s), tools, [[sewing machines]], (from the mid-1950s) the [[F1 submachine gun]], [[L1A1 Self Loading Rifle|L1A1 SLR]], [[KAL1 general purpose infantry rifle]] [[prototype]]s and similar products.\n\nThe Lithgow Small Arms Factory was known to produce their [[single shot]] models 1A and 1B as well as their Model 12 [[repeating rifle|repeater]] under the [[Slazenger]] brand during the 1960s.<ref name=lsmamuseum/>  The factory was first \"corporatised\" as Australian Defence Industries by the [[Hawke Government]], then later sold in 2006.  ADI Lithgow is now owned by [[Thales Australia]] and continues to manufacture the [[F88 Austeyr]] rifle and [[FN Minimi|F89 Minimi]] currently used by the [[Australian military]].<ref name=lsmamuseum/>  \n\nAs a separate entity, not owned or run by the current owners of the factory, the volunteer-run Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum is located at the front of the disused section of site and has a large collection of military and civilian firearms manufactured at the factory and elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lithgowsafmuseum.org.au/index.html|title=Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum|accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref> In 2019, the museum was placed on the UNESCO Australian Memory of the World Register which lists influential collections and documents considered key to [[History of Australia|Australia's history]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lithgowmercury.com.au/story/5876115/small-arms-factory-recognised-in-unesco-world-register/|title=Small Arms Factory recognised in UNESCO World Register|last=Bastow|first=Ciara|date=2019-01-30|website=Lithgow Mercury|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> The museum sees 9,000 annual visitors and is a big draw to the city of Lithgow. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lithgowmercury.com.au/story/6030095/lithgow-small-arms-museum-collection-put-at-risk-with-new-regulation-video/|title=Lithgow Small Arms Museum collection put at risk with new regulation {{!}} Video|last=Bastow|first=Ciara|date=2019-04-11|website=Lithgow Mercury|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\n\n=== Military ===\n\nAlongside the weapons listed below, the factory also produced bayonets, components, barrels, and magazines as well as repairing, modifying, and rechambering weapons. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lithgowsafmuseum.org.au/milproduction.html|title=Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum|website=lithgowsafmuseum.org.au|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n* [[Lee\u2013Enfield|Short Magazine Lee Enfield]], some 50,000 rifles produced with variants including Mk III and Mk IV from 1912 to 1945.\n* [[Vickers machine gun]], 12,500 Mk I, Mk V, and Mk XXI produced from 1929 to 1943.\n* [[Bren light machine gun]], 17,500 produced from 1940 to 1945.\n* [[L1A1 Self Loading Rifle]], 222,773 rifles produced from 1959 to 1986\n* [[L2A1]], 9,557 produced\n* [[L1A1-F1]], 460 produced\n* [[F1 submachine gun]], 25,000 produced from 1962 to 1973\n* [[Austeyr F88]], produced from 1988\n* [[FN Minimi|Minimi F89]], produced from 1989\n\n=== Commercial ===\n\nA broad variety of weapons complemented the factory's military production, but also civilian products such as aircraft parts, golf heads, and tractor components, amongst other things. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lithgowsafmuseum.org.au/comproduction.html|title=Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum|website=lithgowsafmuseum.org.au|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n'''Discontinued firearms:'''\n* Lithgow Model 1 [[.22 caliber|.22]] [[single-shot]] rifle produced from 1945\n* Lithgow Model 1A .22 single-shot rifle\n* Lithgow Model 1B .22 single-shot rifle\n* Lithgow Model 12 .22 [[bolt-action]] 5-shot [[repeating rifle|repeater]] produced from 1947\n* Lithgow Model 12 .22 bolt-action 10-shot repeater (Bibby)\n* Lithgow Model 24 [[.22 Hornet]] cartridge produced from 1949\n* A single shot bolt action shotgun using the [[.410 bore|.410\" cartridge]] (name unknown)\n\n'''Current production firearms:'''\n* Lithgow LA101 CrossOver [[bolt-action]] [[Rimfire ammunition|rimfire]] rifle, available in [[.17 HMR]], [[.22 LR]] and [[.22 WMR]]\n* Lithgow LA102 CrossOver bolt-action [[centerfire]] rifle, available in [[.223 Rem]], [[.243 Win]] and [[.308 Win]]\n* Lithgow LA105 Woomera bolt-action centerfire rifle available, in [[6.5mm Creedmoor]] and .308 Win\n* [[F90 assault rifle|Lithgow F90 Semi Auto/Automatic Military Grade Rifle]], available in [[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lithgowarms.com/f90/|title=F90 Automatic Rifle Family \u2013 Lithgow Arms|website=www.lithgowarms.com|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref>\n** Lithgow F90MBR Modular Bullpup Rifle, available in 5.56\u00d745mm NATO\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Griffiths|first=Tony|title=Lithgow's Small Arms Factory and its People|volume=2 volumes|year=2006|publisher=Toptech Engineering|location=Terrey Hills, New South Wales|isbn=9780975064610}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.lithgowarms.com}}\n* [http://www.lithgowsafmuseum.org.au Lithgow Small Arms Factory Museum Website (not affiliated with Lithgow Arms or Thales)]\n* [http://www.lithgow-tourism.com/smallarms.htm Lithgow Tourism]\n* [http://www.thalesgroup.com/Countries/Australia/Home/ Thales Australia]\n\n[[Category:Military installations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Museums in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Military and war museums in Australia]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Military installations established in 1912]]\n[[Category:Military history of New South Wales]]\n\n\n{{NewSouthWales-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lollipoplollipoplollipop", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spacing around refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lithgow_Small_Arms_Factory"}
{"title_page": "Henry Drummond (1730\u20131795)", "text_new": "'''Henry Drummond''' (1730\u20131795) was a British financier and politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] from 1774 to 1790.\n \nDrummond was the son of [[William Drummond, 4th Viscount Strathallan]] and his wife Margaret Murray, daughter of [[William Murray, 2nd Lord Nairne]]. He became an apprentice to his father's brother [[Andrew Drummond (banker)|Andrew Drummond]], a London banker. Henry Drummond handled a large amount of American business, and acted as financial agent for New Jersey in 1763. In 1759 he became army agent for the [[42nd Regiment of Foot|42nd Foot]] and [[46th Foot]] which were commanded by Murray relatives. By 1761 he was agent for the [[87th Regiment of Foot (Keith's Highlanders)|87th Regiment]] commanded by [[Robert Murray Keith]] and the [[89th (Highland) Regiment of Foot|89th Regiment]] commanded by [[Staats Long Morris]]. In 1765 he went into partnership with Richard Cox, and by 1771 the firm had 18 regiments on their books.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/drummond-hon-henry-1730-5| title= DRUMMOND, Hon. Henry (1730-5), of Charing Cross, London, and The Grange, Hants | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 20 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nDrummond married Elizabeth Compton, daughter of Hon. Charles Compton on 21 March 1761. In 1770 he took over from his cousin John Drummond as partner of [[Thomas Harley]] in the contract for army remittances to North America. John Drummond's health failed in 1772, and  Robert Drummond persuaded Henry to give up his army agency business and return to the bank as third partner. Henry Drummond was a member of a  social group, known as \u2018The Gang\u2019, which included [[Anthony Chamier]], [[Lord Frederick Campbell]], [[William Amherst (British Army officer)|William Amherst]], Sir John Sebright, Thomas Bradshaw, Rigby, Thomas Harley, and R. M. Keith.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nDrummond purchased a parliamentary seat at [[Wendover (UK Parliament constituency)|Wendover]]  from Lord Verney and was returned in 1774 in a by-election as [[Member of Parliament]] for Wendover. He then purchased a seat at [[Midhurst (UK Parliament constituency)|Midhurst]] on the recommendation of Lord North and at the [[1780 British general election|1780 general election]]  was returned  as MP for Midhurst. He retired in 1790. There is no record of any speech by Drummond .<ref name = HOP/>\n\nDrummond died on 24 June 1795.<ref name = HOP/> His son [[Henry Drummond (1762-1794)|Henry]] was also a banker and MP.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Adams (died 1817)|John Adams]]\n | before2 = [[Joseph Bullock]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wendover (UK Parliament constituency)|Wendover]]\n | years =1774\u2013[[1780 British general election|1780]]\n | with  =  [[Joseph Bullock]]  \n| with2  =  [[Thomas Dummer]]  \n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Richard Smith (East India Company officer)|Richard Smith]]\n | after2 = [[John Mansell Smith]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Lord Henry Seymour-Conway|Hon. Henry Seymour-Conway]]\n | before2 = [[John Ord]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Midhurst (UK Parliament constituency)|Midhurst]]\n | years = [[1780 British general election|1780]]\u2013[[1790 British general election|1790]]\n | with  =  [[John St John (died 1793)|Hon. John St John]]  \n| with2  =  [[Sampson Eardley, 1st Baron Eardley|Sir Sampson Gideon]]  \n| with3  =  [[Benjamin Lethieullier]]  \n| with4  =  [[Edward Cotsford]]  \n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Percy Charles Wyndham|Hon. Percy Wyndham]]\n | after2 = [[Charles William Wyndham|Hon. Charles Wyndham]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drummond, Henry}}\n[[Category:1730 births]]\n[[Category:1795 deaths]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n", "text_old": "'''Henry Drummond''' (1730\u20131795) was a British financier and politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] from 1774 to 1790.\n \nDrummond was the son of [[William Drummond, 4th Viscount Strathallan]] and his wife Margaret Murray, daughter of [[William Murray, 2nd Lord Nairne]]. He became an apprentice to his father\u2019s brother [[Andrew Drummond (banker)|Andrew Drummond]], a London banker. Henry Drummond handled a large amount of American business, and acted as financial agent for New Jersey in 1763. In 1759 he became army agent for the [[42nd Regiment of Foot|42nd Foot]] and [[46th Foot]] which were commanded by Murray relatives. By 1761 he was agent for the [[87th Regiment of Foot (Keith's Highlanders)|87th Regiment]] commanded by [[Robert Murray Keith]] and the [[89th (Highland) Regiment of Foot|89th Regiment]] commanded by [[Staats Long Morris]]. In 1765 he went into partnership with Richard Cox, and by 1771 the firm had 18 regiments on their books.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/drummond-hon-henry-1730-5| title= DRUMMOND, Hon. Henry (1730-5), of Charing Cross, London, and The Grange, Hants | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 20 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nDrummond married Elizabeth Compton, daughter of Hon. Charles Compton on 21 March 1761. In 1770 he took over from his cousin John Drummond as partner of [[Thomas Harley]] in the contract for army remittances to North America. John Drummond\u2019s health failed in 1772, and  Robert Drummond persuaded Henry to give up his army agency business and return to the bank as third partner. Henry Drummond was a member of a  social group, known as \u2018The Gang\u2019, which included [[Anthony Chamier]], [[Lord Frederick Campbell]], [[William Amherst (British Army officer)|William Amherst]], Sir John Sebright, Thomas Bradshaw, Rigby, Thomas Harley, and R. M. Keith.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nDrummond purchased a parliamentary seat at [[Wendover (UK Parliament constituency)|Wendover]]  from Lord Verney and was returned in 1774 in a by-election as [[Member of Parliament]] for Wendover. He then purchased a seat at [[Midhurst (UK Parliament constituency)|Midhurst]] on the recommendation of Lord North and at the [[1780 British general election|1780 general election]]  was returned  as MP for Midhurst. He retired in 1790. There is no record of any speech by Drummond .<ref name = HOP/>\n\nDrummond died on 24 June 1795.<ref name = HOP/> His son [[Henry Drummond (1762-1794)|Henry]] was also a banker and MP.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Adams (died 1817)|John Adams]]\n | before2 = [[Joseph Bullock]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wendover (UK Parliament constituency)|Wendover]]\n | years =1774\u2013[[1780 British general election|1780]]\n | with  =  [[Joseph Bullock]]  \n| with2  =  [[Thomas Dummer]]  \n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Richard Smith (East India Company officer)|Richard Smith]]\n | after2 = [[John Mansell Smith]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Lord Henry Seymour-Conway|Hon. Henry Seymour-Conway]]\n | before2 = [[John Ord]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Midhurst (UK Parliament constituency)|Midhurst]]\n | years = [[1780 British general election|1780]]\u2013[[1790 British general election|1790]]\n | with  =  [[John St John (died 1793)|Hon. John St John]]  \n| with2  =  [[Sampson Eardley, 1st Baron Eardley|Sir Sampson Gideon]]  \n| with3  =  [[Benjamin Lethieullier]]  \n| with4  =  [[Edward Cotsford]]  \n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Percy Charles Wyndham|Hon. Percy Wyndham]]\n | after2 = [[Charles William Wyndham|Hon. Charles Wyndham]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drummond, Henry}}\n[[Category:1730 births]]\n[[Category:1795 deaths]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Drummond_(1730%E2%80%931795)"}
{"title_page": "Archeological Site 4-SK-4", "text_new": "{{short description|Prehistoric human settlement  location}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n  | name           = Archeological Site 4-SK-4\n  | image          = Indian Tom Lake Rd.jpeg\n  | caption        = Location of Nightfire Island on a private property adjacent to Otey Ridge in the background\n  | nearest_city   = [[Tulelake, California]]\n  | locmapin       = California#USA\n  | area           = {{convert|2.5|acre}}\n}}\n'''Archeological Site 4-SK-4''', in [[Tulelake, California]], near [[Macdoel, California]], is a stratified [[archeological site]] that was a hunter-gatherer village on the west shores of the [[Lower Klamath Lake]].<ref name=\"ussite\">{{cite web|title=Notice of Inventory Completion: University of Oregon, Oregon State Museum of Anthropology, Eugene, OR|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2009/02/02/E9-2147/notice-of-inventory-completion-university-of-oregon-oregon-state-museum-of-anthropology-eugene-or|accessdate=April 10, 2020 |author=Federal Register, The Daily Journal of the United States Governement||date=February 2, 2009 |}}</ref> The site is located in the heart of the [[Klamath Basin]] wetlands, west of [[Indian Tom Lake]].<ref name=\"site\">{{cite web|last=Garfinkel |first=Alan P. |title=Culture Crisis and Rock Art Intensification:  Numic Ghost Dance Paintings and Coso Representational Petroglyphs |url=http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |accessdate=April 15, 2013 |author2=Geron Marcom |author3=Robert A. Schiffman |date=November 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506092308/http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |archivedate=May 6, 2013 }}</ref> It has also been known as '''Nightfire Island'''<ref>{{cite book |last= Hughes|first= R E|author-link= |date= 1986|title= Diachronic variability in obsidian procurement patterns in northeastern California and southcentral Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Bvjg2LypUowC|location= |publisher= Univ of California Press|page= |isbn=}}</ref> and as '''Sheepy Island'''.  Prehistorically, it served as a camp on a wetland man-made mound and as a ceremonial site.<ref name=howe>Howe, 8-9</ref> The site shows evidence of human occupancy from the peak of the [[Holocene climatic optimum|Hypsithermal era]], approximately 7,000 years ago.<ref>Johnson, L. (1969). Obsidian hydration rate for the Klamath Basin of California and Oregon. Science, 165(3900), 1354-1356.</ref> [[Obsidian]] [[arrowhead]]s are frequent finds, whose varieties include Northern Sided Notched, [[Elko point|Elko type corner notched]], and Gunther type points.<ref>Justice, N. D. (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC Stone Age spear and arrow points of California and the Great Basin] Indiana University Press. Page 174</ref> \n\nExcavations and sampling started in 1966. The site was described by Garth Sampson in a 1985 publication of the [[University of Oregon]], located in [[Eugene, Oregon]].<ref name=\"geoarch\">{{cite journal|last=Sampson|first=C. Garth|title=Nightfire Island: Later holocene lakemarsh adaptation on the western edge of the great basin|journal=Geoarcheology|year=1985|volume=2|pages=247|url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt5wq3p6dd/qt5wq3p6dd.pdf|accessdate=April 5, 2020|doi=}}</ref> Modern Modocs have called the island ''Shapasheni'', meaning \"where the sun and moon live\",<ref name=\"Murguia\">{{cite book |last= Murgu\u00eda|first= Alejandro |author-link= |date= 2002|title= The Medicine of Memory: A Mexica Clan in California|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=DVZfAgAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= University of Texas Press|page= 154-155|isbn=0292778708}}</ref> or \"home of the sun and the moon.<ref>{{cite book |last= Doty|first= Thomas |author-link= |date= 2002|title= Doty Meets Coyote|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=LhuUCwAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= Blackstone Publishing|page= |isbn=1504708334}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOccupation of the Klamath Basin areas may have begun about 6000 BCE.<ref name=\"geoarch\" /> Settlement by [[Modoc people]] on the banks of Sheepy Creek is likely to have begun approximately 4000 years [[Common Era|BCE]],<ref name=\"grayson\" /> shortly after the eruption of [[Mount Mazama]]. Studies of the archeological site's layers shows that volcanic ash formed a layer on the lake bed just below the layer that marks the appearance of occupation by a new village.<ref name=howe /> \n\nThe shallow water level of the marsh, the clay loam, and the basalt rubble basin extended all around and over this settlement point, meant that the Indian pioneers had to carry rocks to strengthen their foundation. After centuries of this procedure, they had built an island of an area approximately {{Convert|2.5|acre||abbr=}}. Surrounded by marshlands, the villagers could fish and hunt for waterfowl.<ref>Kittredge, W. (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U89OpWh0itoC Balancing water: restoring the Klamath Basin]. Univ of California Press. Page 176</ref> The springs that are nearest to Nightfire Island are geothermal waters, adding to the comfort of the villagers. During the dry months, the receding water levels allowed for the establishment of a secure hunting station. Charcoal remains show evidence of cooking pits and cremated burial sites within the island. Bones show an early abundance of duck with additional diversity appearing in later years.<ref name=\"geoarch\" />\n \nFowl droppings on layers in the excavation site show that there were times where the site was abandoned for several hundred years, probably because of the rising of the levels of Indian Tom lake, climate change within the hot and dry middle Holocene, or changes in the Keno fault.<ref name=\"grayson\">Grayson, D. K. (1976). A note on the prehistoric avifauna of the Lower Klamath Basin. The Auk, 93(4), 830-833.</ref> When water levels receded, occupation resumed with the appearance of black charcoal levels from cooking and cremation fires.<ref name=howe />\n\n==Archeology==\nExcavations of archeological site 4-SK-4 have produced large collections of bird, mammal, and fish bones, and large numbers of obsidian technology, particularly Elko points, bone, mortars and other stone artifacts as well as other cultural detritus.<ref name=\"grayson\" /><ref name=\"Murguia\" /> These occupational debris reaches a maximum of 3 meters deep. The lower stratum is [[Lake|lacustrine]], waterway [[diatom]]-rich silt from the original lake floor present during the first occupation of the site. From there, the strata consist of a series of [[silt]], streamland and [[loam]] forming a [[duripan]] horizon.\n\nSamll animals hunted by the villagers were boiled in baskets, larger animals in rock roasting ovens primarily of large basalt rocks. Along with oven rocks, other rocks included broken fragments of [[mortar and pestle]]s and banded stones used for weights. Banded rocks are generally used for outdoor support such as tying down canoes.<ref>{{cite book |last= Carlisle|first= Rodney P. |author-link= |date= 2007|title= Native America from Prehistory to First Contact|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=J7FZggSz3eAC|location= |publisher= ABC-CLIO|page= 177|isbn=1851098291}}</ref> In Nightfire island, banded rocks may have been used for indoor weights since they were found inside the houses and in roasting pits.<ref>Howe, p. 64</ref> The number of these rocks and their weight exceeds the traditional canoe weights and even the weights used by the [[Modoc people]] for the balsa-type rafts. The banded rocks from Nightfire Island show signs of burning mixed with charcoal from cooking fires.<ref>Howe, p. 67</ref> Some stones were used for boiling food in basketry by placing the hot basalt or lava stones into tightly packed woven water-filled baskets.<ref>{{cite book |last= The Library of Native Americans|first= |author-link= |date= 2003|title= The Modoc of California and Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6AjymTpzRTUC|location= |publisher= The [[Rosen Publishing]] Group|page= 19|isbn=1404226605}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of buffalo hide on Nightfire Island suggest the village hunters used obsidian and [[spear-thrower]]s. The most common arrow point found on the site is the [[Cascade point|Cascade-type]]. Additionally, the excavation has produced several pressure-flaking tools made of bone and antler used for projectiles, especially before the bow and arrow were in use.<ref name=\"Howe72\">Howe, p. 72</ref> Stone anvils from the excavation had single and bilateral worn out pits used for [[knapping]] the obsidian to break the [[spall]]s from the rock.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hranicky|first= Wm Jack |author-link= |date= 2013|title= Archaeological Concepts, Techniques, and Terminology for American Prehistoric Lithic Technology|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PSDtkmsHIEsC|location= |publisher= AuthorHouse|page=82, 277 |isbn=1481751743}}</ref> The large amount of anvils found on Nightfire Island suggest they were used for other purposes than knapping, including cracking bones. The side pits are not worn out consistent with the use as a maul or pounding food.<ref name=\"Howe72\" /> \n\nWhile Modocs of the [[Great Basin]] had chipped-stone crescents or lunates,<ref>{{cite book |last= Justice|first= Noel D. |date= 2002|title= Stone Age Spear and Arrow Points of California and the Great Basin|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC|location= |publisher= Indiana University Press|page=116|isbn=0253108837}}</ref><ref>University of California Archaeological Survey, & Berkeley. Archaeological Research Facility. (1960). [https://books.google.com/books?id=0rKVdi0HrusC Reports of the University of California Archaeological Survey]. University of California Archaeological Survey, Department of Anthropology, University of California. p. 44.</ref> their presence has not been confirmed on Nightfire Island. Some smaller versions have been excavated but they are of a different shape and material.<ref name=\"Howe33\">Howe, p. 33 </ref> \n\nExcavations have unearthed structures that suggest buildings similar to [[sweat lodge]]s in Nightfire Island. Carbon-14 dated to approximately 1,500 years ago, these would be the oldest remains of a sweat lodge.<ref name=\"Murguia\" />\n\n===Paleontology finds===\n\n*'''Aves:''' , ''[[Podiceps]]'' spp., ''[[Cygnus (genus)|Cygnus]]'' spp., ''[[Branta]]'' spp., ''[[Anas]]'' spp., ''[[Aythya]]'' spp., ''[[Bucephala (bird)|Bucephala]]'' spp., ''[[Mergus]]'' spp.\n\nThe bird life of Nightfire island includes the following species dated by radiocarbon determinations:<ref name=\"grayson\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Dates and species defined by number of identified specimens\n|-\n!from 4000-3000 BC\n!from 3000-2200 BC\n!from 2020 BC-AD 0\n!from 0-1400 AD\n|-\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (5)\n|[[Common loon]] (17)\n|-\n|[[Horned grebe]] (0)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (1)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (5)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (25)\n|-\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (1)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (5)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (15)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (10)\n|-\n|[[Western grebe]] (1)\n|[[Western grebe]] (2)\n|[[Western grebe]] (28)\n|[[Western grebe]] (280)\n|-\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (5)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (9)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (27)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (51)\n|-\n|[[American white pelican]] (0)\n|[[American white pelican]] (1)\n|[[American white pelican]] (4)\n|[[American white pelican]] (0)\n|-\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (1)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (0)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (0)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (6)\n|-\n|[[Great blue heron]] (1)\n|[[Great blue heron]] (0)\n|[[Great blue heron]] (0)\n|[[Great blue heron]] (4)\n|-\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (0)\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (1)\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (3)\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (2)\n|-\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Tundra swan]] (1)\n|[[Tundra swan]] (6)\n|[[Tundra swan]] (1)\n|[[Tundra swan]] (6)\n|-\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (1)\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (0)\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (2)\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Canada goose]] (2)\n|[[Canada goose]] (4)\n|[[Canada goose]] (16)\n|[[Canada goose]] (6)\n|-\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (3)\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (45)\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (95)\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (52)\n|-\n|[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (3)\n|[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (19)\n|[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (41)\n||[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (51)\n|-\n|[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (1)\n|[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (2)\n||[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (36)\n|[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (14)\n|-\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (0)\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (0)\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (1)\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (112)\n|-\n|[[Canvasback]] (0)\n|[[Canvasback]] (2)\n|[[Canvasback]] (15)\n|[[Canvasback]] (131)\n|-\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (4)\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (7)\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (12)\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (3)\n|-\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (0)\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (0)\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (2)\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (0)\n|- \n|[[Bufflehead]] (3)\n|[[Bufflehead]] (3)\n|[[Bufflehead]] (13)\n|[[Bufflehead]] (25)\n|-\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (17)\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (9)\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (48)\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (92)\n|-\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (0)\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (0)\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (3)\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (103)\n|-\n|[[Common merganser]] (8)\n|[[Common merganser]] (18)\n|[[Common merganser]] (24)\n|[[Common merganser]] (111)\n|-\n|[[Red-breasted merganser]]) (0)\n|[[Red-breasted merganser]]) (1)\n|[[Red-breasted merganser]]) (0)\n|[[Red-breasted merganser]]) (1)\n|-\n|[[Golden eagle]] (1)\n|[[Golden eagle]] (1)\n|[[Golden eagle]] (61)\n|[[Golden eagle]] (0)\n|-\n|[[Bald eagle]]s (3)\n|[[Bald eagle]]s (3)\n|[[Bald eagle]]s (1)\n|[[Bald eagle]]s (1)\n|-\n|[[Hen harrier]] (0)\n|[[Hen harrier]] (0)\n|[[Hen harrier]] (1)\n|[[Hen harrier]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Greater sage-grouse]] (1)\n|[[Greater sage-grouse]] (0)\n|[[Greater sage-grouse]] (4)\n|[[Greater sage-grouse]] (0)\n|-\n|[[American coot]] (20)\n|[[American coot]] (53)\n|[[American coot]] (387)\n|[[American coot]] (1220)\n|-\n|[[Killdeer]] (0)\n|[[Killdeer]] (1)\n|[[Killdeer]] (0)\n|[[Killdeer]] (0)\n|-\n|[[European herring gull]] (0)\n|[[European herring gull]] (0)\n|[[European herring gull]] (0)\n|[[European herring gull]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Great horned owl]]s (0)\n|[[Great horned owl]]s (0)\n|[[Great horned owl]]s (0)\n|[[Great horned owl]]s (1)\n|-\n|[[Snowy owl]] (0)\n|[[Snowy owl]] (0)\n|[[Snowy owl]] (1)\n|[[Snowy owl]] (0)\n|-\n|[[Short-eared owl]] (0)\n|[[Short-eared owl]] (0)\n|[[Short-eared owl]] (0)\n|[[Short-eared owl]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Common raven]] (0)\n|[[Common raven]] (0)\n|[[Common raven]] (0)\n|[[Common raven]] (1)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last= Howe|first= Carrol B|author-link= |date= 1979|title= Ancient Modocs of California and Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=qi0aAQAAIAAJ|location= |publisher= Binford & Mort|page= |isbn=}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 6th millennium BC]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Siskiyou County, California]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Siskiyou County, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Prehistoric human settlement  location}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n  | name           = Archeological Site 4-SK-4\n  | image          = Indian Tom Lake Rd.jpeg\n  | caption        = Location of Nightfire Island on a private property adjacent to Otey Ridge in the background\n  | nearest_city   = [[Tulelake, California]]\n  | locmapin       = California#USA\n  | area           = {{convert|2.5|acre}}\n}}\n'''Archeological Site 4-SK-4''', in [[Tulelake, California]], near [[Macdoel, California]], is a stratified [[archeological site]] that was a hunter-gatherer village on the west shores of the [[Lower Klamath Lake]].<ref name=\"ussite\">{{cite web|title=Notice of Inventory Completion: University of Oregon, Oregon State Museum of Anthropology, Eugene, OR|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2009/02/02/E9-2147/notice-of-inventory-completion-university-of-oregon-oregon-state-museum-of-anthropology-eugene-or|accessdate=April 10, 2020 |author=Federal Register, The Daily Journal of the United States Governement||date=February 2, 2009 |}}</ref> The site is located in the heart of the [[Klamath Basin]] wetlands, west of [[Indian Tom Lake]].<ref name=\"site\">{{cite web|last=Garfinkel |first=Alan P. |title=Culture Crisis and Rock Art Intensification:  Numic Ghost Dance Paintings and Coso Representational Petroglyphs |url=http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |accessdate=April 15, 2013 |author2=Geron Marcom |author3=Robert A. Schiffman |date=November 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506092308/http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |archivedate=May 6, 2013 }}</ref> It has also been known as '''Nightfire Island'''<ref>{{cite book |last= Hughes|first= R E|author-link= |date= 1986|title= Diachronic variability in obsidian procurement patterns in northeastern California and southcentral Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Bvjg2LypUowC|location= |publisher= Univ of California Press|page= |isbn=}}</ref> and as '''Sheepy Island'''.  Prehistorically, it served as a camp on a wetland man-made mound and as a ceremonial site.<ref name=howe>Howe, 8-9</ref> The site shows evidence of human occupancy from the peak of the [[Holocene climatic optimum|Hypsithermal era]], approximately 7,000 years ago.<ref>Johnson, L. (1969). Obsidian hydration rate for the Klamath Basin of California and Oregon. Science, 165(3900), 1354-1356.</ref> [[Obsidian]] [[arrowhead]]s are frequent finds, whose varieties include Northern Sided Notched, [[Elko point|Elko type corner notched]], and Gunther type points.<ref>Justice, N. D. (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC Stone Age spear and arrow points of California and the Great Basin] Indiana University Press. Page 174</ref> \n\nExcavations and sampling started in 1966. The site was described by Garth Sampson in a 1985 publication of the [[University of Oregon]], located in [[Eugene, Oregon]].<ref name=\"geoarch\">{{cite journal|last=Sampson|first=C. Garth|title=Nightfire Island: Later holocene lakemarsh adaptation on the western edge of the great basin|journal=Geoarcheology|year=1985|volume=2|pages=247|url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt5wq3p6dd/qt5wq3p6dd.pdf|accessdate=April 5, 2020|doi=}}</ref> Modern Modocs have called the island ''Shapasheni'', meaning \"where the sun and moon live\",<ref name=\"Murguia\">{{cite book |last= Murgu\u00eda|first= Alejandro |author-link= |date= 2002|title= The Medicine of Memory: A Mexica Clan in California|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=DVZfAgAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= University of Texas Press|page= 154-155|isbn=0292778708}}</ref> or \"home of the sun and the moon.<ref name=\"Murguia\">{{cite book |last= Doty|first= Thomas |author-link= |date= 2002|title= Doty Meets Coyote|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=LhuUCwAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= Blackstone Publishing|page= |isbn=1504708334}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOccupation of the Klamath Basin areas may have begun about 6000 BCE.<ref name=\"geoarch\" /> Settlement by [[Modoc people]] on the banks of Sheepy Creek is likely to have begun approximately 4000 years [[Common Era|BCE]],<ref name=\"grayson\" /> shortly after the eruption of [[Mount Mazama]]. Studies of the archeological site's layers shows that volcanic ash formed a layer on the lake bed just below the layer that marks the appearance of occupation by a new village.<ref name=howe /> \n\nThe shallow water level of the marsh, the clay loam, and the basalt rubble basin extended all around and over this settlement point, meant that the Indian pioneers had to carry rocks to strengthen their foundation. After centuries of this procedure, they had built an island of an area approximately {{Convert|2.5|acre||abbr=}}. Surrounded by marshlands, the villagers could fish and hunt for waterfowl.<ref>Kittredge, W. (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U89OpWh0itoC Balancing water: restoring the Klamath Basin]. Univ of California Press. Page 176</ref> The springs that are nearest to Nightfire Island are geothermal waters, adding to the comfort of the villagers. During the dry months, the receding water levels allowed for the establishment of a secure hunting station. Charcoal remains show evidence of cooking pits and cremated burial sites within the island. Bones show an early abundance of duck with additional diversity appearing in later years.<ref name=\"geoarch\" />\n \nFowl droppings on layers in the excavation site show that there were times where the site was abandoned for several hundred years, probably because of the rising of the levels of Indian Tom lake, climate change within the hot and dry middle Holocene, or changes in the Keno fault.<ref name=\"grayson\">Grayson, D. K. (1976). A note on the prehistoric avifauna of the Lower Klamath Basin. The Auk, 93(4), 830-833.</ref> When water levels receded, occupation resumed with the appearance of black charcoal levels from cooking and cremation fires.<ref name=howe />\n\n==Archeology==\nExcavations of archeological site 4-SK-4 have produced large collections of bird, mammal, and fish bones, and large numbers of obsidian technology, particularly Elko points, bone, mortars and other stone artifacts as well as other cultural detritus.<ref name=\"grayson\" /><ref name=\"Murguia\" /> These occupational debris reaches a maximum of 3 meters deep. The lower stratum is [[Lake|lacustrine]], waterway [[diatom]]-rich silt from the original lake floor present during the first occupation of the site. From there, the strata consist of a series of [[silt]], streamland and [[loam]] forming a [[duripan]] horizon.\n\nSamll animals hunted by the villagers were boiled in baskets, larger animals in rock roasting ovens primarily of large basalt rocks. Along with oven rocks, other rocks included broken fragments of [[mortar and pestle]]s and banded stones used for weights. Banded rocks are generally used for outdoor support such as tying down canoes.<ref>{{cite book |last= Carlisle|first= Rodney P. |author-link= |date= 2007|title= Native America from Prehistory to First Contact|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=J7FZggSz3eAC|location= |publisher= ABC-CLIO|page= 177|isbn=1851098291}}</ref> In Nightfire island, banded rocks may have been used for indoor weights since they were found inside the houses and in roasting pits.<ref>Howe, p. 64</ref> The number of these rocks and their weight exceeds the traditional canoe weights and even the weights used by the [[Modoc people]] for the balsa-type rafts. The banded rocks from Nightfire Island show signs of burning mixed with charcoal from cooking fires.<ref>Howe, p. 67</ref> Some stones were used for boiling food in basketry by placing the hot basalt or lava stones into tightly packed woven water-filled baskets.<ref>{{cite book |last= The Library of Native Americans|first= |author-link= |date= 2003|title= The Modoc of California and Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6AjymTpzRTUC|location= |publisher= The [[Rosen Publishing]] Group|page= 19|isbn=1404226605}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of buffalo hide on Nightfire Island suggest the village hunters used obsidian and [[spear-thrower]]s. The most common arrow point found on the site is the [[Cascade point|Cascade-type]]. Additionally, the excavation has produced several pressure-flaking tools made of bone and antler used for projectiles, especially before the bow and arrow were in use.<ref name=\"Howe72\">Howe, p. 72</ref> Stone anvils from the excavation had single and bilateral worn out pits used for [[knapping]] the obsidian to break the [[spall]]s from the rock.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hranicky|first= Wm Jack |author-link= |date= 2013|title= Archaeological Concepts, Techniques, and Terminology for American Prehistoric Lithic Technology|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PSDtkmsHIEsC|location= |publisher= AuthorHouse|page=82, 277 |isbn=1481751743}}</ref> The large amount of anvils found on Nightfire Island suggest they were used for other purposes than knapping, including cracking bones. The side pits are not worn out consistent with the use as a maul or pounding food.<ref name=\"Howe72\" /> \n\nWhile Modocs of the [[Great Basin]] had chipped-stone crescents or lunates,<ref>{{cite book |last= Justice|first= Noel D. |date= 2002|title= Stone Age Spear and Arrow Points of California and the Great Basin|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC|location= |publisher= Indiana University Press|page=116|isbn=0253108837}}</ref><ref>University of California Archaeological Survey, & Berkeley. Archaeological Research Facility. (1960). [https://books.google.com/books?id=0rKVdi0HrusC Reports of the University of California Archaeological Survey]. University of California Archaeological Survey, Department of Anthropology, University of California. p. 44.</ref> their presence has not been confirmed on Nightfire Island. Some smaller versions have been excavated but they are of a different shape and material.<ref name=\"Howe33\">Howe, p. 33 </ref> \n\nExcavations have unearthed structures that suggest buildings similar to [[sweat lodge]]s in Nightfire Island. Carbon-14 dated to approximately 1,500 years ago, these would be the oldest remains of a sweat lodge.<ref name=\"Murguia\" />\n\n===Paleontology finds===\n\n*'''Aves:''' , ''[[Podiceps]]'' spp., ''[[Cygnus (genus)|Cygnus]]'' spp., ''[[Branta]]'' spp., ''[[Anas]]'' spp., ''[[Aythya]]'' spp., ''[[Bucephala (bird)|Bucephala]]'' spp., ''[[Mergus]]'' spp.\n\nThe bird life of Nightfire island includes the following species dated by radiocarbon determinations:<ref name=\"grayson\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Dates and species defined by number of identified specimens\n|-\n!from 4000-3000 BC\n!from 3000-2200 BC\n!from 2020 BC-AD 0\n!from 0-1400 AD\n|-\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (5)\n|[[Common loon]] (17)\n|-\n|[[Horned grebe]] (0)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (1)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (5)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (25)\n|-\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (1)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (5)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (15)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (10)\n|-\n|[[Western grebe]] (1)\n|[[Western grebe]] (2)\n|[[Western grebe]] (28)\n|[[Western grebe]] (280)\n|-\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (5)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (9)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (27)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (51)\n|-\n|[[American white pelican]] (0)\n|[[American white pelican]] (1)\n|[[American white pelican]] (4)\n|[[American white pelican]] (0)\n|-\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (1)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (0)\